<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Crimson Classic Wins at Fonner Park </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GRAND ISLAND, Neb. (AP) -- A reluctant Ken Shino agreed to ride  
Crimson Classic, and it turned out to be the quickest way for him 
to finally win the $100,000 Bosselman-Gus Fonner Handicap. 
</P>
<P>
	Crimson Classic finished in 1:43 3-5 for a 3/4-length victory in  
the 1 1-16 mile race, which offers Fonner Park's biggest purse. 
</P>
<P>
	Defending champion Battle Mountain was second, followed by  
Skunktail, the horse Shino rode to second-place finishes over the 
last two years. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's one of the races I've been trying to win for a lot of  
years now,'' Shino said. ``I would have liked to have won it on 
Skunk. But things happen. You end up having to ride different 
horses.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Crimson Classic was gritty down the stretch. The win paid  
$60,000 and raised the career earnings of the Kentucky-bred son of 
Sky Classic out of the dam Marianna's Girl to $374,048. 
</P>
<P>
	The posttime favorite in a field of seven at 7-to-5 odds,  
Crimson Classic paid $5, $3.20 and $2.40. Battle Mountain returned 
$3.80 and $2.80. Skunktail paid $2.60 to show. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
