<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NATO VIPs Entertained in Tent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Intimate East Room affairs are all good and  
well for a few dozen NATO VIPs. But for Saturday night's cast of 
hundreds, the White House took its gala for visiting dignitaries 
outside under a South Lawn tent. 
</P>
<P>
	Leaders of both the alliance members and its partner nations --  
along with their ministers and other delegation members -- left 
behind briefings and conferences for an evening of soothing opera. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just a few years ago, a gathering of all the nations here in  
partnership would have been unthinkable,'' President Clinton said 
in his official toast before nearly 900 guests. ``But we are all 
here tonight because we are thinking ... of a future brighter than 
the past, a future of shared values and shared visions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Your presence here is the most vivid demonstration of how much  
our world has changed and changed no doubt for the better,'' NATO 
Secretary General Javier Solana said in his toast. He reminded his 
colleagues that ``principles not only have to be proclaimed but 
have to be defended.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Each leader arrived in limousine at the White House's grand  
foyer, most smiling or waving for the cameras but ignoring the 20 
or so demonstrators across the street who blew whistles and chanted 
anti-NATO slogans in megaphones. 
</P>
<P>
	The inside of the enormous tent resembled a reception hall, from  
the light green bunting draped across the ceilings to the facades 
on the walls with painted doors. Former Sen. Bob Dole and wife 
Elizabeth, Attorney General Janet Reno and Sen. Strom Thurmond, 
R-S.C., mingled among guests from the diplomatic core and military. 
</P>
<P>
	Across town, District of Columbia Mayor Anthony Williams threw  
his own bash for other foreign dignitaries and more than 1,000 
government and community leaders at the National Building Museum. 
</P>
<P>
	Three stages were set up to represent different Washington  
neighborhoods, and the U.S. Navy Band played on a stage with a 
replica of the Capitol dome as the backdrop. Katharine Graham, 
chairman of the executive committee of The Washington Post Co., and 
former Joint Chiefs of Staff Colin Powell, helped welcome guests. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton presented his 18 NATO colleagues each with a  
commemorative medallion and a white porcelain bowl featuring the 
flags of member countries and the presidential seal. Leaders of the 
Partnership for Peace nations received a crystal bridge sculpture, 
while a crystal globe was given to delegation members. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House summoned opera stars Thomas Hampson and Renee  
Fleming to perform for the crowd. Heinz Fricke, music director of 
the Washington Opera since 1993, and the Kennedy Center Opera House 
Orchestra completed the ensemble. 
</P>
<P>
	White House chefs prepared a feast of chicken breast with  
fire-roasted onion, grilled filet of bison and a variety of spring 
vegetables. Gold base plates topped tables adorned in cream table 
cloths. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
