<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> SmithKline Enlists To Sell Avandia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Hoping to ensure a successful launch for its new  
diabetes drug, SmithKline Beecham is taking the unusual step of 
enlisting the help of a rival pharmaceutical company. 
</P>
<P>
	A day after winning support from a key government advisory  
panel, SmithKline Beecham announced an agreement Friday with 
Bristol-Myers Squibb to promote the new drug, Avandia. The drug is 
expected to win final approval in June. 
</P>
<P>
	SmithKline is hoping to tap the expertise Bristol-Myers has  
garnered over the past several years marketing its top-selling 
diabetes drug, Glucophage. For Bristol-Myers, the arrangement helps 
the company retain a competitive position in the diabetes drug 
market after its patent on Glucophage expires in three years. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the deal, the two companies would likely share profits  
generated by Avandia, which promises to fight diabetes with fewer 
liver risks than existing drugs. Analysts expect that Avandia could 
quickly reach sales as high as $1 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The market for diabetes drugs is lucrative in America, where  
some 15 million people suffer from Type 2 or adult-onset diabetes. 
Most patients take a combination of pills, though Avandia and 
Glucophage can be prescribed alone. 
</P>
<P>
	SmithKline President J.P. Garnier said he expects Bristol-Myers  
sales representatives to recommend doctors to prescribe Avandia for 
all new diabetes patients, and as the first drug used in 
combination with Glucophage. He said the companies will not 
actively seek to switch patients from Glucophage to Avandia. 
</P>
<P>
	``We do not see this as a big contradiction,'' Garnier said.  
</P>
<P>
	Bristol-Myers officials said the deal was the quickest way to  
expand diabetes sales. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a great foundation with Glucophage,'' said Donald  
Hayden, president of worldwide medicines at Bristol-Myers. ``We see 
this co-promotion as a further ability to meet unmet needs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Industry analyst Hemant Shah of HKS &AMP; Co. said: ``The deal is  
far more important for Bristol because it allow them to extend the 
life cycle of Glucophage as a combination drug.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As part of the agreement, SmithKline may get the chance to  
co-promote a future Bristol-Myers drug. Other terms of the deal 
were not released. 
</P>
<P>
	New diabetes drugs such as Avandia have been widely anticipated  
since the federal government last month added new warnings to 
Warner-Lambert's Rezulin drug because of patients suffering liver 
failure. Food and Drug Administration officials list 43 Rezulin 
patients who suffered acute liver failure. Of those, 28 died and 
seven needed liver transplants to survive. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
