<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 16:22:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ukraine Seeks Inclusion in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Declaring ethnic Albanians are ``not just  
innocent lambs,'' Ukraine's president Leonid Kuchma said Saturday 
any peace force in Kosovo should include Russian troops and respect 
the Serbian side of the dispute over the province. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana said Russian and Ukrainian  
troops would be welcomed into a peacekeeping force to assure the 
security of refugees returning home after a hoped-for setttlement 
of the Kosovo conflict. 
</P>
<P>
	But Solana said there must be a ``robust force,'' and that means  
having NATO troops at its core. 
</P>
<P>
	Kuchma, a former rocket designer seeking re-election in October,  
attended the NATO summit here as head of one of the larger European 
countries that remain outside the growing trans-Atlantic alliance. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have got no right to stand aside,'' Kuchma said of the  
Balkans conflict. ``The main point is that all of us work in the 
same direction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	NATO and Ukraine established a joint commission in 1997. Kuchma  
met Saturday with allied leaders to formalize the use of a former 
Soviet military base in western Ukraine, Yavoriv, for NATO training 
exercises. It also will be used for Ukrainian and Romanian forces 
to make joint preparations to respond to emergencies in eastern and 
central Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	In an APTN interview, Kuchma, whose foreign policy generally has  
been balanced between Russia and Western Europe, offered his 
formula for a quick end to the conflict in Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	He said NATO should end its bombing campaign simultaneously with  
withdrawal of Serb troops from Kosovo under arrangements that also 
would permit return of refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	It is essential that an armed peacekeeping force, established  
through the United Nations, move into the province, Kuchma said, 
comprising troops from nations that did not participate in the NATO 
bombing campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``We should try to respect the Serbian side and respect the  
territorial integrity of Kosovo,'' Kuchma said, and should not 
blame only Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic for the conflict 
in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Albanians also are to blame,'' he said. ``The Albanians  
are not just innocent lambs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kuchma said he is willing to go to Belgrade to try to arrange a  
settlement. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would not go there just to breathe the fresh air,'' he said.  
``There should be a certain formulation before such a trip.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For a peace force to succeed, he said, it must gain the  
confidence of the Serbs. And that, he said, means participation of 
Russian troops is essential. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, at a joint news conference, Solana said ``to guarantee  
the security of the refugees, I cannot imagine a robust force under 
any other form'' than the one proposed by NATO. 
</P>
<P>
	Solana praised Kuchma's ``tireless diplomatic efforts'' and said  
the Ukrainian president and NATO ``are both committed to a lasting 
political settlement.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
