<DOCNO> APW19990424.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 15:12:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Friends Mourn Teen Killed in Colo. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLETON, Colo. (AP) -- They lined up next to the pulpit, aside  
the white casket covered with the felt-tipped signatures and 
farewell wishes that will be buried with her. And one by one, they 
told Littleton and the nation the story of her life. 
</P>
<P>
	On police lists, she was Rachel Scott, 17, victim. But these  
young men and women knew somebody far more resonant: a prom date 
who was trying to quit smoking. An actress and budding playwright 
who talked of decorating the apartment she'd have one day. Rachel 
Joy Scott -- the girl who befriended strangers, the girl with the 
ideal middle name. 
</P>
<P>
	And suddenly she was gone. On Saturday, weeping and hollow-eyed,  
they mourned her in a sad parade, their reminiscences melting 
together into a portrait of a truly extraordinary girl. 
</P>
<P>
	One sobbing blond girl told of how Ms. Scott would always  
jump-start her car in the Columbine High School parking lot. A 
muscular boy said he wished he could have protected her. Her 
handsome prom date, Nick Baumgart, thanked her for sharing her 
life. 
</P>
<P>
	``A truer friend you couldn't find,'' said Baumgart, who took  
her to the prom just a week ago. ``You could be having the worst 
day of your entire life. All she had to do was smile.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Scott was one of 12 students slain by Dylan Klebold and Eric  
Harris in their rampage through Columbine on Tuesday. Her funeral 
was held at Trinity Christian Center, a church less than a 
half-mile from Columbine. Its front door affords a clear view of 
the school library. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rev. Bruce Porter lamented the removal of prayer from  
America's public schools but said the violence at Columbine may 
have changed matters. 
</P>
<P>
	``Prayer was re-established in our public schools last  
Tuesday,'' Porter said to applause. ``What the judiciary couldn't 
do, what the churches couldn't do, the children did themselves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Scott's teachers remembered a dedication and verve that  
elevated her from the crowd. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was so proud of that girl. She was talented and beautiful,  
and I know that she's with us still,'' said Paula Reed, Ms. Scott's 
forensics teacher. ``But she took part of me with her.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The choreographed funeral, complete with a montage of family  
pictures from Ms. Scott's earlier childhood and happier times, 
featured a continuous tape loop of Celine Dion's ``My Heart Will Go 
On,'' the ``Titanic'' theme song. A female mime and a youth group 
also performed. 
</P>
<P>
	In one picture, Ms. Scott mugged with a fedora and bright  
lipstick; another showed her grinning with friends, her face 
flushed. 
</P>
<P>
	Just a few days before the shooting, Ms. Scott wrote in her  
cousin's yearbook that ``it's hard to find God through these 
halls.'' But she urged her cousin, Sarah Scott, to keep on trying. 
</P>
<P>
	Dozens of teens in the audience wiped streaming tears from their  
faces and dropped their heads into their hands. One diminutive girl 
buried her head in the burly shoulder of her companion. 
</P>
<P>
	Friends signed Ms. Scott's closed casket by the dozen in black  
felt-tip marker, leaving their words with her permanently. Some 
promised they'd see her in heaven. ``You are my hero,'' one wrote. 
Others tried to make sense of the death. Her parents simply said 
goodbye. 
</P>
<P>
	``Honey, you are everything a mother could ask the Lord for in a  
daughter. I love you so much!'' her mother wrote. And from her 
father: ``I love you. Dad. Forever.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Scott, friends said, knew her own mind. She was a spirited  
actress in school plays, a devout Christian who wanted to go on a 
mission this summer to Africa. And she had a playful streak a mile 
wide. If she wanted to wear a sailor hat or pajama bottoms to 
school, why not? 
</P>
<P>
	``If she liked it, she would wear it,'' said Heide Johnson, her  
friend since fourth grade. ``She didn't care what other people 
thought of her. She just wanted to be true to herself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One day, she showed up at school with especially strange attire  
-- for a reason. 
</P>
<P>
	``She just wanted to see how people responded to her. She wanted  
to know who her true friends were,'' Ms. Johnson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Early last week, Ms. Johnson and Ms. Scott saw each other and  
made plans to get together after school one day soon. It was the 
last time Ms. Johnson saw her friend alive. 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, outside the school, Ms. Scott's red Acura remained  
parked where she left it Tuesday morning. It had become a shrine, 
barely visible beneath flowers, cards, balloons and stuffed 
animals. 
</P>
<P>
	On the hood sat a small Teddy bear, clutching a sign:  
</P>
<P>
	``Never forget.''  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990424.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 14:12:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Leaders Show Change in Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Italy's premier was a rising young Communist  
in the years of turbulent student protest. The Spaniard serving as 
NATO's secretary general campaigned against the alliance earlier in 
his career. A young Bill Clinton marched against the Vietnam War 
and managed to not get drafted. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the NATO leaders now exercising air power were far more  
interested in the likes of flower power in their youth. 
</P>
<P>
	``They have shed their old skins like some mammals do,'' says  
historian Henry Graff, ``and they're wearing new ones.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Time and circumstance have brought together a diverse collection  
of leaders who cut their teeth in the European antinuclear 
movement, protested war and in some cases opposed the very 
institution they now celebrate and wish to expand. 
</P>
<P>
	The change is explained in part by the efforts of leaders such  
as President Clinton and British Prime Minister Tony Blair to move 
political parties with liberal traditions closer to the center. 
Graff, professor emeritus at Columbia University, says it also is 
an example of people on the outside adjusting to the realities of 
leadership once they take power. 
</P>
<P>
	``It isn't that they got smarter,'' he said. ``The trouble with  
all of them is that they read history. Each one sees in himself a 
Churchill or Franklin Roosevelt.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Moreover, an air campaign launched with the humanitarian  
justification of safeguarding ethnic Albanians in Kosovo is easier 
for leaders of various political leanings to support than a war for 
territory. ``That fits the position of all these guys ... a kind of 
moral grandeur,'' Graff said. 
</P>
<P>
	Their early years did not necessarily point to this sort of  
rendezvous with destiny. 
</P>
<P>
	Italian Premier Minister Massimo D'Alema, 49, was raised on the  
precepts of Marxism, became a Communist Party youth leader and rose 
through the party even as he exerted a moderating influence on it. 
As a boy of 13, he gave flowers to Palmiro Togliatti, a party 
founder who had railed against his country's decision to join NATO 
at its creation. 
</P>
<P>
	Now that same party has a different name along with a commitment  
to free-market ideas. And Italy, though one of the more nervous 
partners in the campaign, is now a prime base for NATO bombers 
hitting Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	Germany's hawkish defense and foreign ministers were antiwar  
activists in the 1960s. Gerhard Schroeder, 55, the first German 
chancellor without personal memory of World War II, was prominent 
in the 1980s movement against the deployment of U.S. nuclear 
missiles in Europe. And he opposed the Vietnam War while taking no 
active part in protests. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was never a 68er,'' he says, referring to a year of  
particular social turmoil. ``It was all too theoretical for me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As an opposition Socialist politician in the late 1970s and  
early 1980s, Javier Solana, now 56, campaigned against Spain's 
entry into NATO. Now he is the alliance's secretary general. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was wrong about NATO,'' Solana said once when asked about  
his harsh remarks in the past about the organization and the United 
States. ``What do you do when you are wrong? Change. That is what I 
did, change.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Socialists ultimately changed their position about NATO  
after winning power and gradually led Spain into full membership 
after a referendum. 
</P>
<P>
	Blair, 45, came to Parliament in 1983, when the Labor Party had  
a left-wing, antiwar platform that included scrapping Britain's 
nuclear weapons. His foreign minister, Robin Cook, was an outspoken 
pacifist in the 1980s; now second to none in the alliance in 
pushing for resolve in the bombing. 
</P>
<P>
	For Americans, differences in the Vietnam generation are no more  
apparent than in the divergent paths of the president and NATO's 
top military commander in their youth. Like Clinton, 52, Army Gen. 
Wesley Clark, 54, grew up in Arkansas and went off to Oxford. But 
Clark toured Britain making speeches supporting the war and then 
went to Vietnam to fight in it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
