who was trying to quit smoking. An actress and budding playwright 
who talked of decorating the apartment she'd have one day. Rachel 
Joy Scott -- the girl who befriended strangers, the girl with the 
ideal middle name. 
</P>
<P>
	And suddenly she was gone. On Saturday, weeping and hollow-eyed,  
they mourned her in a sad parade, their reminiscences melting 
together into a portrait of a truly extraordinary girl. 
</P>
<P>
	One sobbing blond girl told of how Ms. Scott would always  
jump-start her car in the Columbine High School parking lot. A 
muscular boy said he wished he could have protected her. Her 
handsome prom date, Nick Baumgart, thanked her for sharing her 
life. 
</P>
<P>
	``A truer friend you couldn't find,'' said Baumgart, who took  
her to the prom just a week ago. ``You could be having the worst 
day of your entire life. All she had to do was smile.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Scott was one of 12 students slain by Dylan Klebold and Eric  
Harris in their rampage through Columbine on Tuesday. Her funeral 
was held at Trinity Christian Center, a church less than a 
half-mile from Columbine. Its front door affords a clear view of 
the school library. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rev. Bruce Porter lamented the removal of prayer from  
America's public schools but said the violence at Columbine may 
have changed matters. 
</P>
<P>
	``Prayer was re-established in our public schools last  
Tuesday,'' Porter said to applause. ``What the judiciary couldn't 
do, what the churches couldn't do, the children did themselves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Scott's teachers remembered a dedication and verve that  
elevated her from the crowd. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was so proud of that girl. She was talented and beautiful,  
and I know that she's with us still,'' said Paula Reed, Ms. Scott's 
forensics teacher. ``But she took part of me with her.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The choreographed funeral, complete with a montage of family  
pictures from Ms. Scott's earlier childhood and happier times, 
featured a continuous tape loop of Celine Dion's ``My Heart Will Go 
On,'' the ``Titanic'' theme song. A female mime and a youth group 
also performed. 
</P>
<P>
	In one picture, Ms. Scott mugged with a fedora and bright  
lipstick; another showed her grinning with friends, her face 
flushed. 
</P>
<P>
	Just a few days before the shooting, Ms. Scott wrote in her  
cousin's yearbook that ``it's hard to find God through these 
halls.'' But she urged her cousin, Sarah Scott, to keep on trying. 
</P>
<P>
	Dozens of teens in the audience wiped streaming tears from their  
faces and dropped their heads into their hands. One diminutive girl 
buried her head in the burly shoulder of her companion. 
</P>
<P>
	Friends signed Ms. Scott's closed casket by the dozen in black  
felt-tip marker, leaving their words with her permanently. Some 
promised they'd see her in heaven. ``You are my hero,'' one wrote. 
Others tried to make sense of the death. Her parents simply said 
goodbye. 
</P>
<P>
	``Honey, you are everything a mother could ask the Lord for in a  
daughter. I love you so much!'' her mother wrote. And from her 
father: ``I love you. Dad. Forever.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Scott, friends said, knew her own mind. She was a spirited  
actress in school plays, a devout Christian who wanted to go on a 
mission this summer to Africa. And she had a playful streak a mile 
wide. If she wanted to wear a sailor hat or pajama bottoms to 
school, why not? 
</P>
<P>
	``If she liked it, she would wear it,'' said Heide Johnson, her  
friend since fourth grade. ``She didn't care what other people 
thought of her. She just wanted to be true to herself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One day, she showed up at school with especially strange attire  
-- for a reason. 
</P>
<P>
	``She just wanted to see how people responded to her. She wanted  
to know who her true friends were,'' Ms. Johnson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Early last week, Ms. Johnson and Ms. Scott saw each other and  
made plans to get together after school one day soon. It was the 
last time Ms. Johnson saw her friend alive. 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, outside the school, Ms. Scott's red Acura remained  
parked where she left it Tuesday morning. It had become a shrine, 
barely visible beneath flowers, cards, balloons and stuffed 
animals. 
</P>
<P>
	On the hood sat a small Teddy bear, clutching a sign:  
</P>
<P>
	``Never forget.''  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
