<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 05:21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Georgia Wins Women's Gymnastics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Georgia edged Michigan to win its fifth  
NCAA gymnastics championship on Friday night at the University of 
Utah's Huntsman Center. 
</P>
<P>
	The Gym Dogs repeated as national champs, but the Super Six  
competition wasn't decided until Georgia's last competitor on 
balance beam, senior Jenni Beathard, bailed out classmate Karin 
Lichey by avoiding a fall on Georgia's last beam routine. 
</P>
<P>
	Lichey, Georgia's top-ranked individual gymnast, had  
uncharacteristically fallen earlier. Beathard scored a 9.8. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every championship is totally different. There was so much  
heart and so much guts on this team, they weren't going to quit,'' 
Georgia coach Suzanne Yoculan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Georgia's 196.850 score also extended its winning streak to 67  
straight meets. The Gym Dogs haven't lost a meet since the 1997 
NCAA championships and are the first repeat winners since Utah in 
1994 and 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Lichey, who finished second in the all-around Thursday night,  
bounced back from her fall on beam to score a 9.95 on floor to help 
her team post a 49.250. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was so excited because everyone else was excited,'' Lichey  
said. ``This year has been full of so many ups and downs, but we 
never quit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Bulldogs became the 12th top seed in history to win the  
championship. 
</P>
<P>
	Michigan finished second with a score of 196.550, its best  
finish in school history. The Wolverines tied for second with 
Alabama in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Michigan opened the competition on beam, traditionally the most  
difficult event psychologically. Kathy Burke was the only Wolverine 
to fall, and the team scored an impressive 49.0. 
</P>
<P>
	Alabama, which finished third last year, finished third again  
with a 195.95. After a strong bars set to open the meet, the 
Crimson Tide moved to beam, where two of its athletes fell. 
</P>
<P>
	That took them out of the championship hunt, but Alabama  
responded by posting a 49.025 on floor and a 49.125 on vault. 
Alabama made its 11th top-three finish in 12 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Arizona State, the 10th seed coming into the tournament,  
finished fourth with a score of 195.90. UCLA, which fell twice on 
beam, finished fifth with 195.85 and Nebraska was sixth with 
194.80. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bruins couldn't seem to mentally overcome the problems  
suffered by teammate Alison Stoner, who injured her knee during her 
floor routine in UCLA's first rotation. Stoner, who may have torn 
several ligaments in her knee, was taken to University Hospital for 
X-rays. 
</P>
<P>
	Georgia was also the top seed in 1993 and 1998 when it  
prevailed. The Gym Dogs can increase its title haul Saturday night 
during the individual event finals. Seven athletes will compete, 
with Lichey competing in all four events. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
