<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Colo. Victim Released From Hospital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Makai Hall was shot in the leg, 10 bullet holes in  
all. But when a homemade explosive landed near him and several 
other injured students, he didn't hesitate. 
</P>
<P>
	``I threw it away from us,'' the 16-year-old Columbine High  
School student said quietly, his eyes cast downward. 
</P>
<P>
	The dark-haired teen didn't want to be portrayed as a hero. He  
told reporters at St. Anthony Central Hospital on Friday he just 
wanted to give thanks for the outpouring of support and be with his 
friends and family. 
</P>
<P>
	``I found it really easy to think of all the bad things that  
have come from this, but it really makes you feel good to think of 
the human compassion and how everyone came together to help us 
out,'' Hall said. ``I just wanted to thank everyone. It's made me 
feel really good and it's helped my recovery very much. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even though it's a great tragedy, I'm not going to let it  
bring me down. I'm going to use it to motivate myself,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hall spoke to reporters before being discharged from the  
hospital. He arrived at the briefing in a wheelchair. A blue and 
white ribbon was pinned to his green fleece pullover. His face was 
young and clear, except for an injury to the left side of his jaw 
where he had been hit with shrapnel. 
</P>
<P>
	Hall was one of 23 people injured when two students dressed in  
long, black trench coats blazed into the school Tuesday, showering 
it with bombs and bullets. Fifteen people, including the two 
killers, died. 
</P>
<P>
	``I remember a teacher running into the library screaming that  
some kids had guns,'' Hall said. ``Everybody got under their desks 
really quick and then soon after that, not more than five minutes 
after that two people came in and started shooting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hall knew one of the shooters, Dylan Klebold, and had him in a  
French class the year before. He said Klebold was an ``all right 
guy. ... He never treated me bad.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hall said he doesn't know if he looked Klebold in the eye when  
Klebold and fellow gunman Eric Harris stormed into the library 
where Hall was hiding under a desk. 
</P>
<P>
	``They fired a number of shots and one hit me and I lay on the  
ground. They moved towards me and that's all I can remember,'' Hall 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hall said his friend Patrick Ireland, who dangled desperately  
from a library window before being saved by SWAT team members, 
tried to help him. But Hall was reluctant to say much about his 
friend or some other events. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are some things I just don't feel that people should  
know. It's a tragedy, yeah, but how far do you have to go with 
it,'' said Hall, who was joined by his father, David, and his 
mother, Sue. 
</P>
<P>
	Hall is expected to make a full recovery. He said he's focusing  
on his emotional well-being. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to see some of the people that were there and I want to  
go to some of the services and stuff and start healing 
emotionally,'' Hall said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just going to keep active and use it to motivate myself.''  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
