<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Americans Expect More Shotings  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Four out of five Americans expect more  
shootings like the attacks at a Colorado high school to occur 
elsewhere in the country over the next year or so, says a new poll. 
In another poll, about that many said high school shootings are a 
sign something is seriously wrong in this country. A CNN/USA 
Today/Gallup poll taken this week indicated 79 percent believe 
Tuesday's shootings in Littleton, Colo., that left 15 dead -- 
including the two assailants -- are a sign of serious national 
problems rather than isolated incidents. In a CBS poll, 80 percent 
said they expect more shootings. 

</P>
<P>
	5 Charged in Texas Shooting Plot  
</P>
<P>
	WIMBERLEY, Texas (AP) -- Five junior high school students have  
been charged with conspiring to kill students and teachers in an 
alleged plot similar to the Colorado rampage, authorities said. The 
boys, all age 14, were taken into custody yesterday and are being 
held on juvenile charges of conspiracy to commit murder, conspiracy 
to commit arson and conspiracy to manufacture explosives, said 
sheriff's Sgt. Allen Bridges. Officials believe the boys had been 
planning since January to carry out an assault at Danforth Junior 
High School in Wimberley, a 450-student school about 40 miles 
northeast of San Antonio. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Strikes Yugoslav Army Base  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO warplanes today bombarded the  
home base of Yugoslav forces operating in Kosovo, less than a day 
after the United States announced it was sending more troops to 
Albania to bolster the campaign against Slobodan Milosevic's forces 
in the province. Also, American diplomats have begun drafting a 
U.N. Security Council resolution calling for the demilitarization 
of Kosovo and an international military force. The move appears 
aimed at silencing European critics who had complained that the 
alliance ignored the United Nations in launching its air campaign 
March 24. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Accused of `Anti-China Farce'  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- China accused Washington today of engaging in an  
``anti-China farce,'' one day after U.N. Human Rights Commission 
failed to adopt a U.S. resolution censuring Beijing's human rights 
record. Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Sun Yuxi said the 
commission's 22-17 vote to dismiss the resolution showed worldwide 
recognition of China's human rights progress. ``The United States 
stands alone in this anti-China farce. The motion against China was 
naturally doomed to fail,'' Sun said in a statement read to 
reporters and splashed on the front page of People's Daily, the 
Communist Party's flagship newspaper. 

</P>
<P>
	New Computer Bug To Strike Monday  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A virus that can erase a computer's hard-drive  
and prevent the equipment from restarting is poised to strike on 
Monday, but experts say off-the-shelf antivirus software can 
prevent infection, and several companies are offering free 
inoculation tools on their Web sites. The virus has been dubbed 
Chernobyl because its most common version was programmed to 
activate on computers using Windows 95 and Windows 98 on Monday, 
the 13th anniversary of the nuclear disaster in Ukraine. 

</P>
<P>
	South Korea Workers Support Strike  
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- Thousands of workers and students  
marched today in downtown Seoul, protesting a government plan to 
break up a six-day old subway strike. The 10,000 protesters rallied 
in a park, then marched 2 miles along four lanes of an eight-lane 
boulevard to a Roman Catholic church where subway union leaders 
were seeking refugee from court-issued arrest warrants. Thousands 
of police were dispatched but no serious clash occurred. Traffic 
backed up for hours. 

</P>
<P>
	Protesters Disrupt Airline Meeting  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Northwest Airlines Corp. ended its annual  
meeting early after protesters frustrated with drawn-out 
negotiations between the company and its flight attendants began 
yelling and making speeches. The talks have been ongoing for 2 1/2 
years and are in mediation. Chairman Gary Wilson ended the meeting, 
which was held in New York, and said he would individually answer 
the stack of written questions that had been submitted by employees 
and shareholders. 

</P>
<P>
	John Elway To Announce Retirement  
</P>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- John Elway, the comeback quarterback who led the  
Denver Broncos to Super Bowl victories in the last two years of a 
brilliant NFL career, has told friends he is retiring after 16 
seasons, The Associated Press has learned. Sources who spoke on 
condition of anonymity told the AP the 38-year-old has told family 
and friends that he won't be back for the 1999 season and 
considered making an announcement this past week. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
