<DOCNO> APW19990424.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 11:43:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court To Hear La. School Board Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- The U.S. Supreme Court hears arguments Monday  
in a Louisiana dispute about how school board members are elected, 
a case that will affect the federal government's ability to 
challenge election laws that hurt minority voting power. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the court is an 8-year-old lawsuit challenging how the  
district map is drawn for election of Bossier Parish's 12 school 
board members. 
</P>
<P>
	For decades, Bossier Parish's 12-member school board was totally  
white. In 1996, two blacks were elected. A third, first appointed 
to fill a vacancy, was elected last year to a full term. 
</P>
<P>
	Each was chosen from majority white districts, and  
Superintendent Jane E. Smith says that fact alone should be enough 
to sway justices to end the suit. 
</P>
<P>
	``We followed the law and achieved what the Justice Department  
wanted us to do without gerrymandering,'' Smith said. 
</P>
<P>
	The court's eventual decision will determine how easy or  
difficult it will be for the Justice Department to reject proposed 
election law changes that hurt minority voting power in nine 
Southern states and parts of other states which must get federal 
approval of changes in voting practices under the Voting Rights Act 
of 1965. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for George Price and the local chapter of the NAACP say  
despite the recent election of blacks to the school board, 
minorities are still not adequately represented. 
</P>
<P>
	When the 1990 census required a redrawing of the board's  
election map, Price, then president of the civil rights group, 
proposed creating two districts with black majorities. 
</P>
<P>
	``There had never been a black elected to the parish school  
board in the parish's history,'' said Price, 55, an administrative 
director of environmental services at LSU Medical Center in 
Shreveport. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were concerned about the mounting problems, the declining  
number of black teachers and administrators, the overall plight of 
black students.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Instead of doing as Price asked, the school board adopted the  
same districts that had been adopted by the police jury, the 
parish's chief governing body. 
</P>
<P>
	The police jury's plan had already received the Justice  
Department's approval, but the school board's duplicate of it did 
not. Justice Department lawyers decided this time it would dilute 
minorities' voting strength. 
</P>
<P>
	A legal battle ensued, and in 1997 the Supreme Court used the  
Bossier Parish case to make it harder for the Justice Department to 
withhold approval of proposed election changes. 
</P>
<P>
	The justices then sent the case back to a three-judge federal  
court in Louisiana so it could decide whether federal approval can 
be withheld for a discriminatory ``purpose'' other than leaving 
minority voters worse off. 
</P>
<P>
	``We drew the lines according to state law,'' Ms. Smith said.  
``They wanted us to gerrymander to ensure that two minorities would 
be elected. Gerrymandering is unconstitutional.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Patricia Brannan, who represents Price and will argue before the  
high court, said the board's current makeup does not worsen the 
condition of minority voters in light of the Supreme Court's 
ruling. ``But we believe evidence shows there was discrimination, 
which was part of the motivating purpose behind the plan, and we 
think that should be sufficient enough to bar it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Price said he could not understand the continued opposition to  
creating at least two minority districts in a parish whose 
population is about 20 percent black. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990424.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 12:41:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clinton Pushes Violence Prevention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton will ask Congress for money  
and stricter gun laws to help stem school violence such as the 
attack last week at a Colorado high school in which 15 people were 
killed. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said in his weekly radio address Saturday that he wants  
to keep guns away from juveniles and will seek $12 million for 
emergency teams ``to help communities respond when tragedy 
strikes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The attack in Littleton, Colo., was the seventh at schools  
around the country in two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Gun-control legislation the president is requesting would focus  
on keeping guns out of the hands of juveniles and providing money 
to help schools hire counselors and mentors and buy metal 
detectors. 
</P>
<P>
	``The government must take responsibility,'' Clinton said in the  
address. ``We must do more to prevent violence in our schools.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said his Safe Schools Bill would crack down on gun shows  
and illegal gun trafficking, prohibit ``violent juveniles'' from 
being able to buy guns and close ``the loophole that lets juveniles 
own assault rifles.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We must do more to keep guns out of the hands of violent  
juveniles,'' Clinton said. ``We must do more to prevent violence in 
our schools.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The bill provides money to school systems across the nation to  
help prevent repeats of last week's Littleton violence, in addition 
to the $12 million to finance emergency teams to help communities 
in similar crises. 
</P>
<P>
	Colorado Gov. Bill Owens, who delivered the Republicans' weekly  
radio address, said the episode in a quiet Denver suburb warns of 
problems eating at the American way of life. 
</P>
<P>
	``Events like this one warn us there is a virus loose within our  
culture,'' Owens said. ``Too may of our young people are 
susceptible to it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Owens urged parents to play more active roles in their  
children's lives, particularly to pay more attention to what their 
children may be watching on television, what video games they play, 
what World Wide Web sites they log onto. 
</P>
<P>
	``Do you know if your child has a home page?'' Owens asked. ``Do  
you know what is on your child's home page, or whom they talk with 
on the Internet? 
</P>
<P>
	``If not, please find out.''  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990424.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 12:41:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
