<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Grabs Massacre-Related Sites </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- A Massachusetts man says he rushed to register  
three World Wide Web addresses after the Colorado school shooting 
rampage -- all to keep them out of the wrong hands. 
</P>
<P>
	Jose Troche of Taunton managed to register trenchcoatmafia.net  
and trenchcoatmafia.org, but someone beat him by several minutes to 
the name trenchcoatmafia.com. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't want someone to use those names to come up with a  
neo-Nazi Web page, saying 'Let's blow up the world,''' said Troche, 
29, who owns a beeper company. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the person who registered trenchcoatmafia.com was also  
trying to prevent misuse of the name. 
</P>
<P>
	Two teens, dressed in black trench coats, killed 13 people and  
injured 23 others before killing themselves at Columbine High 
School in Littleton, Colo. Both boys belonged to a group that 
called themselves the Trenchcoat Mafia. 
</P>
<P>
	Troche said he wanted to prevent others from making money off  
the 'trenchcoatmafia' name. He said two people interested in buying 
the Web addresses have already approached him. He claimed one man 
offered $30,000 and another offered $35,000. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	LAKE STEVENS, Wash. (AP) -- The Trenchcoats used to be anything  
but controversial. 
</P>
<P>
	The mellow a capella singing group was booked as the headliner  
for a May 13 concert at the high school Performing Arts Center in 
this town about 25 miles north of Seattle. 
</P>
<P>
	Now that two members of the group calling itself the Trenchcoat  
Mafia has been blamed for the shooting deaths of 15 people at 
Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo., the concert is getting a 
second look. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let's face it,'' Mayor Jay Echols said Friday. ``We've been  
struck by lightning.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The group of cleancut men in their late 20s and early 30s don't  
even wear trench coats, Echols said. 
</P>
<P>
	Echols said the band's manager has been out of town and  
unavailable for discussion of the matter. 
</P>
<P>
	A discussion is likely Tuesday at a meeting of the town's  
Performing Arts Commission, the mayor added. 
</P>
<P>
	``I totally understand that everyone wants to respect what  
happened in Littleton,'' said Echols, ``but I am concerned about 
what to do because we have already sold tickets and we have a 
contract with the band.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Compounding the group's problems, a student mistakenly gave the  
Seattle singing group's Web address -- www.trenchcoats.com -- as the 
site of those who planned the shootings and booby trapping of the 
school with bombs. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our server has just been lighting up like a Christmas tree  
since Wednesday night,'' bass singer Kerry Dahlen told The Seattle 
Times. ``It's been pretty interesting traffic.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	WATERFORD TOWNSHIP, Mich. (AP) -- Three Oakland County students  
asked that their high school's flag be flown at half-staff in 
respect for the victims of last week's mass killings at a Colorado 
high school. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials with the Waterford district refused, saying it would  
violate flag etiquette. 
</P>
<P>
	Matt Ivory, Matt Redmond and Aaron Hiner asked that the flag be  
lowered at Mott High School, as it has been at countless other 
schools since last Tuesday's shootings. 
</P>
<P>
	Ivory said the principal told him it could not be done.  
</P>
<P>
	``He said `no' because we have to have an order from the  
president or governor to fly it at half-staff,'' Ivory told The 
Oakland Press of Pontiac. ``I called Congressman (Dale) Kildee, and 
a guy checked it out and said the president or governor can issue 
an order, but it is up to the organization or group to decide if 
they want to fly the flag lowered.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	PORTSMOUTH, N.H. (AP) -- The Colorado school shootings have  
prompted Portsmouth schools to ban black trench coats and dark 
clothing associated with shock singer Marilyn Manson and the gothic 
movement. 
</P>
<P>
	``When kids come back from vacation, they better not even think  
about wearing Marilyn Manson'' or anything else related to the 
gothic movement -- a look defined by white face paint and black or 
dark-dyed hair, said Superintendent Suzanne Schrader. 
</P>
<P>
	``Parents are welcome to challenge me in court,'' Schrader told  
the Portsmouth Herald. 
</P>
<P>
	Schrader said she hopes banning divisive clothes will help  
students feel less of a separation from one another. 
</P>
<P>
	Parent Anastasia Parker disagrees with the ban. Her daughter  
Rachel went to the media last year because students were tormenting 
her for her Marilyn Manson-wear. 
</P>
<P>
	``Marilyn Manson is 75 percent of my daughter's wardrobe,'' she  
said. ``Does this mean I have to go out and buy all new clothes?'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
