<DOCNO> APW19990424.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 09:13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US Veteran Seeks Mercy for Killing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- A hardscrabble childhood put Manuel Babbitt  
on the receiving end of life's hard blows. Two bloody tours of duty 
in Vietnam programmed him to deliver them. 
</P>
<P>
	The fractured halves of Babbitt's life blew apart one foggy  
December night in 1980. He broke into the home of Leah Schendel, 
hammering her with punches that shattered her dentures, split the 
skin on her forehead to the bone and jolted her 78-year-old heart 
into fatal arrest. 
</P>
<P>
	On May 4, a day after he turns 50, Babbitt is scheduled to pay  
for that crime with his life. 
</P>
<P>
	His family and his lawyers say Babbitt, who was awarded a Purple  
Heart in a rare death-row ceremony, is a casualty of war. 
</P>
<P>
	They are asking for mercy from another Vietnam vet, Gov. Gray  
Davis, on the grounds that Babbitt was in the grip of a flashback 
when he attacked Mrs. Schendel; in an eerie detail, Babbitt wrapped 
a leather strap around her ankle like a soldier tagging battlefield 
dead. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was Vietnam that killed Leah Schendel,'' says Babbitt's  
sister, Donna Kendricks. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're feeling betrayed,'' adds brother Bill Babbitt, the man  
who first suspected Manuel Babbitt of murder -- and went to police 
for help. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Schendel's relatives have a problem with Babbitt's  
execution, too. They want to know why it has taken so long. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're tired,'' says John Rizzotti, Mrs. Schendel's  
great-grandson. ``He was clearly guilty back then; he's clearly 
guilty now. This man deserves to die, there is no way around it.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Manuel Pina Babbitt's alcoholic father, an immigrant from Cape  
Verde off the western coast of Africa, beat his children with a 
strap he made himself, three strips at the bottom for extra sting. 
</P>
<P>
	Heat, food and clothing were scarce at the family's tumbledown  
home in Wareham, Mass.; when the children were big enough to carry 
a box, they worked picking the New England cranberry bogs. 
</P>
<P>
	Babbitt left school illiterate at age 17. In 1967, he failed the  
Marines screening exam. The second time, the recruiter helped him. 
</P>
<P>
	The defining moment of Babbitt's life, his defenders say, was  
the January 1968 siege of Khe Sanh, 77 days of bombardment, mud and 
misery. 
</P>
<P>
	After a while, wrote Navy Chaplain Ray W. Stubbes, many young  
recruits ``developed a flat, blank expression we called 'the 
thousand-yard stare.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Babbitt was wounded in March when two rockets exploded next to  
him. 
</P>
<P>
	Khe Sanh, Babbitt said this week, ``made a ... teen-ager into a  
person who has a side of him that he didn't understand at the time 
-- anxiousness and a sadness that was even sadder than it was before 
he got there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He remembers loading shells filled with thousands of darts. ``A  
bunch of little tiny nails hit little tiny humans and all the 
humans fell. There'd be nothing but blood and guts on the landscape 
and that was the kind of things I had to look at.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	In 1969, ``the Manny that came back from overseas was nuts,''  
childhood friend Phil Gomes told defense lawyers. 
</P>
<P>
	He was discharged in 1970 for ``instability.''  
</P>
<P>
	In March 1973, he was arrested for robbery. He ended up in a  
mental hospital, where he later attempted suicide after learning 
that his wife of five years was leaving him. He was paroled in 1975 
and moved to Providence, R.I. 
</P>
<P>
	Babbitt started a new family with a new girlfriend.  
</P>
<P>
	But soon, he became the neighborhood crazy. He wore battle  
fatigues and would crouch in the middle of the street like a 
soldier on patrol. He once ran through the house, screaming ``We've 
got to get the baby out!'' 
</P>
<P>
	In January 1980, he was accused of raping and beating a  
prostitute. He was acquitted. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1980, the family sent Babbitt to live with brother Bill in  
Sacramento. They hoped to jump-start his life. 
</P>
<P>
	On Dec. 18, 1980, fog hung low over Sacramento as it had in Khe  
Sanh. Sometime after 10 p.m., drunk and stoned, Babbitt walked 
along a brightly lit strip; he would later tell doctors the car 
headlights looked like incoming aircraft. He reached the complex 
where Mrs. Schendel was watching TV, probably a war movie called 
``Tokyo Joe.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When she was found the next morning, Mrs. Schendel was nude from  
the waist down. A mattress had been pulled over the top half of her 
body, a tea kettle placed on her pelvis and a leather strap tied 
around her ankle. She died of a heart attack. 
</P>
<P>
	Less than 24 hours later, Babbitt attacked a 60-year-old woman,  
but broke off when a friend rushed out. 
</P>
<P>
	Babbitt says he has no memory of the attacks.  
</P>
<P>
	Defense lawyers believe the fog, the drugs, contact with an  
Asian vet during the day, and the war movie propelled Babbitt back 
to the kill-or-be-killed world of combat. They say his efforts to 
cover the body mirror the battlefield practice of covering the dead 
with whatever is at hand. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	On March 20, 1998, a Marine officer pinned a Purple Heart on  
Babbitt's chest. Shackled by manacles, Babbitt bent at the waist, 
bringing his forehead to his hand in a stiff salute. 
</P>
<P>
	Thirteen months later, he approaches death philosophically.  
</P>
<P>
	``I've never begged for my life -- it's just a life,'' he said.  
``For the time I have been on this planet it hasn't been a very 
happy situation.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
