<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pennsylvania Marks School Shooting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EDINBORO, Pa. (AP) -- A year ago today, 14-year-old Andrew Wurst  
opened fire on a banquet hall full of his eighth-grade classmates, 
killing a teacher and wounding two students. 
</P>
<P>
	The attack destroyed students' sense of security, and the year  
that has passed hasn't restored the loss. 
</P>
<P>
	``My one daughter can't walk across the back patio yet where he  
bled to death,'' said James Strand, referring to teacher John 
Gillette. ``I would have thought a year would have eased some of 
that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If the experience here is any guide, the people of Littleton,  
Colo., are facing a long emotional convalescence, a period when 
seemingly little things can unexpectedly bring back large fears. 
</P>
<P>
	Melissa Hoover, a high school freshman who attended the dance  
last year that Wurst attacked, recalled how a simple scheduling 
statement triggered tears. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was an announcement that a trial was coming up for Andy,  
and I was sitting next to my friend and she started bawling her 
eyes out,'' she said. ``I've got a lot of friends who are really 
upset about it and cry every time it comes up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pain exists close to the surface calm for many of Edinboro's  
5,000 residents. 
</P>
<P>
	Robbie Zemcik, 15, who was shot in the toe at the dance, tries  
not to think about Wurst, the dance -- or what happened this week in 
Colorado. Choking up, he asked not to be told about the shootings 
at Columbine High School. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd rather not know,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Students were dedicating a memorial garden to Gillette today and  
planning to hold a prayer vigil. 
</P>
<P>
	Wurst's attorney, Phil Friedman, said his client committed the  
shooting but has a mental illness that makes him believe he is the 
only real person alive. Wurst has pleaded innocent, and no trial 
date has been set. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoover sat in a vacant lot after school with two 16-year-old  
friends, Nick Ferguson and Levi Kuczaj. Both boys are sophomore 
punk-rock fans who pride themselves on not fitting in. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've seen this town go to hell,'' Ferguson said. ``That kid  
went goofy last year. The school came down on us real hard. We're 
kids. We should be allowed to be kids.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The boys rattled off a list of friends they say have been  
disciplined for minor offenses since the attack. One was kicked out 
of school for repeated backtalk; others are on probation for 
breaking light bulbs, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's forcing us to grow up faster. And when you grow up  
faster, you don't grow up right,'' Kuczaj said. 
</P>
<P>
	Therese Walter, superintendent of the school district, agreed  
the schools have become more strict, and she says most parents are 
grateful. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
