<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Georgia Wins Night Gymnastics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Defending champion Georgia stayed on  
course for its fifth national title by winning the night session in 
the NCAA Gymnastics Championships Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Gym Dogs, Michigan and Nebraska will compete in Friday's  
Super Six competition at the University of Utah's Huntsman Center. 
UCLA, Alabama and Arizona State qualified in the afternoon session. 
</P>
<P>
	Georgia's team score of 197.025 topped both sessions. The Gym  
Dogs closed the competition with a stunning 49.400 combined score 
on the beam and confirmed their status as Friday's team to beat. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are a lot of teams that are a lot deeper than Georgia,  
but I don't think any team digs as deep as Georgia,'' Gym Dogs 
coach Suzanne Yoculan said. ``They just won't quit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Utah's Theresa Kulikowski became the first freshman to win the  
individual all-around title since Kentucky's Jenny Hansen in 1993. 
Kulikowski posted an overall score of 39.675, edging Georgia senior 
Karin Lichey (39.575). 
</P>
<P>
	But the night session's biggest surprise came when the Utes,  
winners of a record nine national championships, fell three times 
on the beam and failed to qualify for the Super Six for the second 
time in three years. Utah (195.475 points) finished fourth, 0.75 
points behind Nebraska (196.225) for the final spot. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's kind of a bittersweet moment, because I'd like to  
celebrate as a team,'' Kulikowski said. ``We all put in the work 
together. It's kind of tough right now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	UCLA and Alabama were the highest-ranked teams in the afternoon  
session, and didn't disappoint. Despite serious miscues on beam, 
UCLA (196.425 points) and Alabama (194.950) both easily advanced 
into the Super Six. 
</P>
<P>
	``We haven't competed like that on balance beam all year,''  
Alabama coach Sarah Patterson said of her team's season-low 47.850 
beam score, which included three falls. ``The first day is always a 
lot of nerves. The pressure is so much to get to (Friday) night.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Joining Alabama and UCLA was Arizona State (194.525), the  
surprise team of the afternoon. The Sun Devils needed a 48.275 on 
vault -- their final event -- to pass LSU for the final spot in the 
Super Six. 
</P>
<P>
	They got it when Amy Shelton, their last competitor, registered  
a 9.775. 
</P>
<P>
	``As you could see tonight, vaulting is not our strongest event,  
so I was pretty nervous,'' Arizona State coach John Spini said. 
</P>
<P>
	Michigan performed best in floor exercises, posting a team score  
of 49.375, the highest of the day. Sarah Cain and Lisa Simes each 
finished with all-around scores of 39.275 to lead the Wolverines. 
</P>
<P>
	Nebraska knocked out the host Utes despite not winning any of  
the night session events. The Huskers' Heather Brink was third in 
the night all-around rankings with a score of 39.400. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bruins' Heidi Moneymaker was the highest-scoring  
all-arounder in the afternoon session and finished third in the 
overall standings behind Kulikowski and Karin Lichey. 
</P>
<P>
	Moneymaker needed a 9.775 on beam, her final event, to tie  
Alabama's Andree Pickens for the all-around lead. Pickens already 
had finished the competition with a 39.45, but Moneymaker's smooth 
9.875 propelled her into the lead at 39.55. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's amazing what adrenaline can do,'' said Moneymaker, or  
``Cash,'' as her teammates call her. 
</P>
<P>
	During last Friday's practice, the junior sprained both ankles  
while practicing her floor routine. Despite overcoming the nagging 
injury, she wasn't completely satisfied with her performance. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think I performed to perfection like I'd like to, but  
I think I had a solid meet,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Moneymaker had a 9.85 on vault, 9.95 on bars, 9.875 on beam and  
9.875 on floor. 
</P>
<P>
	Louisiana State, Stanford and West Virginia failed to qualify in  
the afternoon session, while Penn State and Florida will join Utah 
on the sidelines from the night session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
