<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Morris Abandons Comeback at LPGA  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STOCKRIDGE, Ga. (AP) -- Stomach churning and emotions spent,  
Marianne Morris picked up her ball after missing an 18-inch putt 
and walked off the course Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	She could go no further.  
</P>
<P>
	Playing in her first tournament since her brother was shot to  
death in a robbery, Morris dropped out of the LPGA's Chick-fil-A 
Charity Championship midway through the second round. 
</P>
<P>
	Morris opened with a 5-under-par 67, putting her just two  
strokes off the lead, but she had bogeys on the first two holes 
Saturday and never recovered. She withdrew with a 42, having 
bogeyed six of nine holes at Eagles Landing Country Club south of 
Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everything went right yesterday,'' said her mother, Barbara  
Morris, tears streaming down her cheeks. ``Nothing went right 
today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Morris' caddie, Jeff King, said the golfer had a queasy stomach,  
but her condition seemed more emotional than physical as she played 
her first tournament in two months. 
</P>
<P>
	She hasn't been able to eat and had a restless night of sleep  
after her remarkable opening round. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just going to take time,'' her mother said. ``This is her  
job. She loves it. But it's hard right now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After missing the short par putt at 18 -- she played the back  
nine first -- Morris stopped off at the clubhouse to inform 
officials of her withdrawal. 
</P>
<P>
	Her playing partners, Rachel Hetherington and Jane Crafter,  
waited for a few minutes at No. 1 before Morris pulled up on a cart 
to tell she couldn't finish the round. Both gave her a hug and 
Morris, red-eyed, hopped back in the cart and returned to the 
locker room. 
</P>
<P>
	``At least she was able to salvage some pride and go out with a  
67 on her scorecard,'' King said. ``There was no reason to stay out 
there. If she was playing decent, maybe she would have tried to 
finish out. But there's no sense staying out there and punishing 
yourself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There's been enough of that already. Mike Morris, her mentor,  
business partner and best friend, was gunned down Feb. 21 in a 
robbery at the suburban Atlanta golf shop they owned together. 
</P>
<P>
	The 34-year-old golfer considered quitting the tour after her  
brother's death, unsure if the game still had meaning. But two 
weeks ago, she picked up a sand wedge and started chipping. 
</P>
<P>
	Morris decided to resume her career at the same event where her  
brother served as her caddie a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was a bad place to start again,'' Barbara Morris said.  
``She can't eat. She can't keep anything down. There's still stuff 
she's got to settle as far as business. She's got a lot on her 
mind.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That made the first round even more remarkable. Morris made a  
couple of 25-foot birdie putts and another from 20 feet, feeling 
each time that her brother's presence was guiding the ball into the 
cup. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel like I'm playing for both of us,'' she said after the  
round. ``Maybe I'll be more like him -- play aggressive and enjoy 
being out there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the burden was too much to bear two days in a row.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure there was pressure,'' Barbara Morris said. ``She  
wanted to do so well after yesterday.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She was consoled by her mother in the locker room, then emerged  
with golf shoes in hand and headed to her car. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really don't feel like saying anything,'' she said, eyes  
still red. ``I'm sorry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Morris, who has yet to win in nine years on the LPGA tour, hopes  
to play next weekend at the Myrtle Beach Classic in South Carolina, 
her mother said. There is still grieving and healing to do, but 
maybe the worst is over. 
</P>
<P>
	``All in all, she's got to be proud of herself,'' King said.  
``This was a big step.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
