<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Indians Off to Flying Start </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- As the 298th straight sellout crowd files  
through the exits at Jacobs Field in a sea of smiling Chief Wahoo 
caps and red, white and blue Indians garb, there is little 
celebrating. 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Thome hit another 400-foot-plus homer into the right-field  
seats. Roberto Alomar made another great play behind second base. 
The bullpen did its job. The Indians beat the Oakland Athletics 
5-1. 
</P>
<P>
	Ho-hum.  
</P>
<P>
	It's much the same downstairs in a subdued Cleveland clubhouse.  
The CD player is off, and while a small group of Indians players 
sit at a table eating, most of the starters are across the hall 
pumping iron and pounding treadmills in the Tribe's 
state-of-the-art strength and conditioning room. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, the Cleveland Indians are all business. This year,  
the Indians are taking nothing for granted. This year, anything 
short of winning the World Series is a failure. 
</P>
<P>
	Don't say it too loud, but this year, the 1999 Indians don't  
want to be like Cleveland teams of the past four years. No, this 
season, the Indians want to be like the '98 New York Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	And so far, Cleveland is doing a pretty good imitation of the  
World Series champions, who won a record 125 games last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Indians, challenged by manager Mike Hargrove to win 100  
regular-season games AND the World Series, are off to one of their 
best starts ever. Entering Saturday, they were 12-3 and leading the 
AL Central, a k a Comedy Central, by 3 1/2 games. 
</P>
<P>
	Cleveland already has had an eight-game winning streak and a  
couple of comeback wins that brought back memories of 1995, when 
the Indians seemed to win every game in their final at-bat. 
</P>
<P>
	``These guys continue to show how good they are night in and  
night out,'' Hargrove said following one such dramatic victory over 
the A's. 
</P>
<P>
	These guys may have the best 1-through-9 lineup in baseball, and  
were leading the majors in virtually every offensive category going 
into the weekend. They still don't have a legitimate No. 1 starter 
-- not yet anyway -- but their starters were a combined 7-1 to start 
the season. They have the majors' deepest bullpen and may have the 
best middle infield in history. 
</P>
<P>
	However, what has been most impressive about Cleveland's fast  
start is how the team is doing the little things -- moving up 
runners, hitting the cutoff man -- to win. Just like a certain AL 
East team did last season. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're just doing everything very well right now,'' Thome said.  
</P>
<P>
	After the Indians' batting average and runs scored dropped  
significantly last season from the year before, Hargrove wanted his 
players to be more selective at the plate. Instead of ripping the 
first pitch that's close to the strike zone, the Indians are being 
finicky. They're sitting back and waiting. Patient hitters make 
pitchers make mistakes. 
</P>
<P>
	It's a tactic the Yankees used so effectively last season. They  
wore out opposing starters and then teed off on thin bullpens. 
</P>
<P>
	So what's the deal. Have the Indians copied a page from New  
York's '98 playbook? 
</P>
<P>
	``No, no, no,'' Hargrove insists. ``We're trying to be like the  
Indians. We have a lot of intelligent hitters in this lineup who 
are patient.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Intelligent and intimidating, that's the Indians.  
</P>
<P>
	With leadoff hitter Kenny Lofton followed in the batting order  
by Omar Vizquel and Robbie Alomar -- both switch-hitters -- the 
Indians are scoring runs early and often. In their first 13 games, 
the Indians outscored opponents in the first four innings 48-17. 
</P>
<P>
	Lofton and Alomar are among the league leaders in walks, and  
when they've gotten on, Jim Thome and Manny Ramirez, who leads the 
majors in RBIs, have been driving them in. 
</P>
<P>
	Travis Fryman, Richie Sexson, Wil Cordero and Sandy Alomar round  
out a Cleveland lineup that hasn't given opposing pitchers a 
moment's rest. 
</P>
<P>
	``I faced the Yankees last year, and they were very good. This  
lineup could be a little tougher,'' Oakland's Kenny Rogers said 
after losing to Cleveland. 
</P>
<P>
	Cleveland's defense is another big reason the Indians have owned  
April. 
</P>
<P>
	Robbie Alomar has stopped grounders up the middle and run down  
popups that were singles the past 2 1/2 years as the Indians tried out 
16 different second baseman to play alongside Vizquel. 
</P>
<P>
	During Cleveland's recent homestand, the Indians avoided at  
least three losses with great defense. Lofton threw out runners at 
the plate in two games with Sandy Alomar blocking the plate 
perfectly both times. 
</P>
<P>
	``On paper, this club has a chance to be the best defensive club  
we've had since I've been here,'' Hargrove said. 
</P>
<P>
	He has had some special teams in his nine seasons in Cleveland,  
including one that came within two outs of winning it all in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	This year's team is being compared with the '95 Indians, a young  
group that had Albert Belle and attitude. Hargrove said that while 
this year's Indians may not have the same swagger, it has a 
confidence similar to the '95 team, which finished 100-44 and won 
the Central by 30 games. 
</P>
<P>
	Cleveland clearly showed some attitude Friday night, with two  
bench-clearing brawls in a 7-6 victory over Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	The first came when Cleveland starter Jaret Wright hit Darren  
Lewis in the right shoulder in the fifth inning. Boston reliever 
Rheal Cormier retaliated by hitting Thome with a pitch in the ribs 
an inning later, setting off the second brawl. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not saying this team isn't cocky,'' Hargrove said.  
``There's a difference between arrogance and cocky. This team has 
the same belief in itself as the '95 team, but the difference is 
that this team is not as arrogant as the '95 team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There is an air of quiet confidence about this year's Indians  
that's similar to last year's Yankees -- they're good and they know 
it. And unlike the past few Cleveland teams, this one seems to have 
a single-minded sense of commitment. 
</P>
<P>
	Players are arriving at the ballpark early and staying late. The  
only lines you'll find after the game are at the Stairmasters, not 
at the buffet table. 
</P>
<P>
	During spring training, Cleveland's players were given T-shirts  
with the words: ``100+ Go Hard or Go Home'' printed on the back. 
Hargrove has come under criticism for setting the 100-win goal for 
the team but felt it was necessary to keep the Indians motivated. 
</P>
<P>
	Whatever's behind the Indians' fast start, it's working.  
</P>
<P>
	``They believe in themselves and they believe in each other,''  
Hargrove said. ``And they play hard.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
