<HEADLINE> Soldiers' Bodies Leave for Dover </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT CAMPBELL, Ky. (AP) -- Soldiers with reddened eyes fought  
tears and family members and friends wept openly Saturday as the 
bodies of seven soldiers killed in a helicopter crash left Fort 
Campbell for Dover Air Force Base, Del. 
</P>
<P>
	A military band played somber music under a gray sky as seven  
black hearses passed. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today we grieve the loss of seven young heroes, seven mighty  
warriors,'' said Lt. Col. Douglas Carver, chaplain of the 101st 
Airborne Division (Air Assault). 
</P>
<P>
	The Black Hawk helicopter toppled into a patch of trees early  
Thursday, killing seven and injuring four others. A team from the 
U.S. Army Safety Center at Fort Rucker, Ala., continues to 
investigate. 
</P>
<P>
	Those killed were members of the 5th Battalion, 101st Aviation  
Regiment and 6th Battalion (Pathfinder), 101st Aviation Regiment, 
159th Aviation Brigade. 
</P>
<P>
	At Dover, the soldiers' bodies will be prepared for burial in  
their hometowns. 
</P>
