<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Record Number of Farmers Seek Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- With many states once again close to depleting  
money available for farm loans, Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman 
is urging Congress to move quickly to pass emergency funding. 
</P>
<P>
	``Congress must act,'' Glickman said late last week. ``We're  
going to be out of money or are (already) out of money.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The farm credit problem has been brewing for months as farmers  
try to prepare for the spring planting season. Low prices last 
season, affected by the Asian economic crisis and lagging exports, 
left farmers in a serious economic pinch. 
</P>
<P>
	States have reported record numbers of farmers coming in for  
loans, which are administered by state offices of USDA's Farm 
Service Agency. 
</P>
<P>
	``Demand is significantly in excess of the demand of last  
year,'' Glickman said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration has proposed $153 million in  
emergency money for the Agriculture Department. Most of the money 
would be used for direct loans or loan guarantees for an estimated 
10,000 producers unable to get credit from private sources. 
</P>
<P>
	But the money, part of a $1.3 billion supplemental bill that  
also includes hurricane aid for Central America, has stalled as 
lawmakers battle over proposed GOP cuts to offset the spending. 
</P>
<P>
	The money could be further slowed as lawmakers debate an  
emergency funding measure that deals with U.S. efforts in Kosovo, 
according to some congressional aides. 
</P>
<P>
	To help the situation, Glickman earlier this month authorized  
shifting $30 million allocated for other uses to temporarily ease 
the loan situation. 
</P>
<P>
	Just over 3 weeks later, that temporary money has also been  
depleted, Glickman said. 
</P>
<P>
	``That money is already gone. It's gone,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton in early March signed a stopgap measure that  
allowed $450 million, originally targeted for another program, to 
be used for farm loans. But demand has exceeded funding. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, officials in Arkansas, which was hit hard by last  
year's drought, said they received about $26 million from the 
government covering about 226 new loans. But USDA officials in 
Arkansas say another $55 million is needed. 
</P>
<P>
	Arkansas' Farm Service Agency approved nearly $130 million in  
guaranteed and emergency loans just in the first half of this 
budget year, a 132 percent increase over 1998, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Moser, a farm loan manager in Nebraska's Wayne County, said  
his office was told by state officials that ``maybe another week to 
two weeks is probably about all the funding that's available.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The lack of funds comes as his office is trying to deal with a  
50 percent increase in the number of loan requests. 
</P>
<P>
	``The demand has definitely been greater than in the past,''  
Moser said. ``We've had to shift some priorities around and maybe 
not complete some of the day-to-day things we normally would 
complete. We're just letting those slide until we have some time to 
get to them.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
