<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Strickland Charged in Drunk Driving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Rod Strickland of the Washington Wizards was  
arrested on charges of drunken and reckless driving early Saturday 
-- three weeks after his probation ended for a 
driving-while-impaired conviction. 
</P>
<P>
	Strickland was pulled over by police who said his gold Mercedes  
Benz was speeding on a District of Columbia street at about 3:45 
a.m. Police said he ran three red lights and changed lanes without 
signaling. 
</P>
<P>
	Strickland was given a sobriety test and ``apparently did not  
pass,'' Police Commander Charles Fonville said. 
</P>
<P>
	Strickland was booked at a precinct and released on  
recognizance. He has a May 7 court date. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Wizards organization is disappointed ... because Rod has  
been exceptional this year in terms of the fans and his commitment 
to the franchise,'' general manager Wes Unseld said. ``We hope to 
garner more information, but for now the situation is in the hands 
of the legal authorities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Strickland was stopped about six hours after the Atlanta Hawks  
defeated the Wizards 89-78, Washington's fourth successive loss. 
Strickland, who averages 15.7 points a game, scored 10 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Strickland joined the NBA in 1988 and came to Washington in a  
1996 trade with Portland. 
</P>
<P>
	On April 3, 1998, he was convicted of driving while impaired and  
was fined and ordered to complete a driver's alcohol-awareness 
program. He also had to perform 30 hours of community service and 
serve a year's probation. 
</P>
<P>
	District of Columbia Superior Court Judge John Hess dismissed a  
disorderly conduct charge stemming from Strickland's early-morning 
arrest on Sept. 3, 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Strickland's latest arrest was the second in two days of an NBA  
star on drunken-driving charges. In Houston, Rockets forward 
Scottie Pippen was accused of running a stop light. Police said he 
failed a field sobriety test and refused to take a Breathalyzer 
test. Pippen denied being drunk. 
</P>
</TEXT>
