<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Notes From NATO Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- For the signing of a declaration reaffirming  
their 50-year alliance, President Clinton led NATO leaders as host, 
stepping to a red carpet lined by 20 stony-faced flag bearers. His 
own Cabinet, seated off to the side in an auditorium filled with 
foreign delegations, rose to applaud. 
</P>
<P>
	For the others, the standing part of the ovation only caught on  
in a slow trickle, as officials in front rows happened to glance 
over their shoulders to see the back rows on their feet. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Friday's ceremony was translated on the spot into 10 languages --  
English, French, Czech, German, Greek, Hungarian, Italian, Polish, 
Spanish and Turkish. And even though most of the leaders spoke in 
English, organizers took no chances. 
</P>
<P>
	When an announcer instructed the leaders on stage -- 19 of the  
world's most powerful men -- to turn and face the flags, a stage 
director rushed to the foot of the podium and frantically twirled 
his fingers at them. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Too many late nights plotting the campaign against Yugoslavia?  
</P>
<P>
	Ninety minutes and 20 speeches seemed too much for the  
battle-fatigued Clinton. Right around speaker No. 7, Iceland's 
Prime Minister David Oddsson, the president betrayed the 
eyes-closing, head-flopping-forward symptoms of a man dozing off. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's most monumental struggle to stay alert came as Prime  
Minister Wim Kok of the Netherlands (No. 11) took the lectern. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton put his chin in his hand, crossed and uncrossed his  
legs, propped his elbows on his knees. But nothing, not even the 
click-clicking of photographers close by at stage left, could keep 
his eyes open. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's posture sprung ramrod straight and his face bore an  
envious smirk, when his friend, British Prime Minister Tony Blair, 
46, opened his remarks with the announcement: ``I am younger than 
NATO.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The highly competitive Clinton is 52.  
</P>
<P>
	But Hungary's Prime Minister Viktor Orban, a newcomer to NATO,  
had everyone beat. He celebrated his 35th birthday just last week. 
</P>
<P>
	After giving his speech, the boyish Orban folded his notes into  
his pocket, turned to Blair, let out a deep breath and raised his 
eyebrows as if to say, ``Whew!'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Forget the U.S. Senate. NATO may be the world's most exclusive  
men's club. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the 100 U.S. and foreign officials seated according to rank  
in the Andrew Mellon Auditorium's front five rows, Albright was the 
only woman. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The powerful world assembly turned some of Washington's own  
power brokers into starry-eyed tourists. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Barbara Mikulski, D-Md., took a cheap, disposable camera to  
the front of the room and insistently gestured for the Czech 
foreign minister and a NATO undersecretary to get Albright to turn 
and face the camera. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Could former Polish President Lech Walesa still be smarting from  
his 1995 defeat at the polls by Aleksander Kwasniewski? 
</P>
<P>
	When Kwasniewski, leader of another new NATO member, was  
introduced, Walesa, who was seated in the third row, did not clap. 
He faintly -- and belatedly -- tapped one hand against his 
translation handset. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The ornate Andrew Mellon Auditorium, with its grand columns  
lined by crushed oysters, is the same room where President Truman 
and his Western counterparts signed the 1949 treaty creating NATO. 
</P>
<P>
	Organizers had the leaders' gold chairs reupholstered for  
Friday's occasion, and the polished-cherry wood lectern and 
matching signing table were made new by Hargrove Inc. of Maryland -- 
``designed to fit in with the overall look and feel of the room.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That room, then called the Departmental Auditorium, is also  
where draft numbers were drawn for young American men during World 
War II. 
</P>
</TEXT>
