<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 05:21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Critics Worry Over Cable Colossus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Will Ma Bell become Ma Cable?  
</P>
<P>
	Fifteen years after the government broke up the telephone  
monopoly, critics worry that AT&AMP;T's $58 billion offer to buy 
MediaOne, the nation's fourth-largest cable TV operator, could 
create a new colossus controlling cable rates, Internet access and 
phone service. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T contends its proposal to buy Media One actually would spark  
competition, forming a powerful rival to the regional phone 
monopolies and driving local phone rates. AT&AMP;T plans to use cable 
systems to deliver local and long-distance phone service, 
high-speed Internet access and interactive entertainment to 
millions of U.S. homes. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T launched its bid Thursday to thwart an existing agreement  
by cable competitor Comcast to buy MediaOne. Comcast and MediaOne 
remained silent on the offer Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	If AT&AMP;T succeeds in outbidding Comcast, regulators are sure to  
closely scrutinize the transaction more closely than AT&AMP;T's 
recently completed purchase of another giant cable company 
Tele-Communications Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Acquiring both TCI and MediaOne would make AT&AMP;T -- already the  
nation's largest telecommunications company -- also its largest 
cable operator. It would have ownership stakes in cable systems 
that could be hooked up to nearly half the homes in the United 
States, observers say. 
</P>
<P>
	``AT&AMP;T obviously was sad to lose its telephone monopoly and is  
doing everything possible to rebuild it in the cable industry 
instead,'' said Gene Kimmelman, co-director of Consumers Union in 
Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	He said that the deal would give AT&AMP;T disproportionate influence  
over cable TV rates and the type of entertainment, news and other 
programming seen by many cable subscribers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Communications Commission is considering limiting  
the number of customers a single cable company can control 
nationwide and could issue a final decision this summer. 
</P>
<P>
	Several years ago, the FCC planned to forbid a single cable  
company from owning systems that cover more than 30 percent of all 
U.S. cable customers. The rule was never put into effect because of 
concern about its legality. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal appeals court in Washington is expected to consider  
the constitutionality of such a limit. 
</P>
<P>
	Several anti-trust experts said Friday they believed that  
federal regulators would permit an AT&AMP;T-MediaOne deal. They pointed 
to the approval of the AT&AMP;T-TCI merger last month and Bell 
Atlantic's acquisition last year of Nynex, a rival Baby Bell. 
</P>
<P>
	Moreover, federal officials have favored deals that trigger new  
local phone competition. Three years after a telecommunications law 
took effect that was intended to generate consumer rivalry and 
drive down rates, local phone companies retain their monopolies and 
rates haven't dropped. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a given on antitrust laws that competition must be  
protected. So long as there's adequate competition, larger size is 
not inherently bad,'' said Robert Burka, an antitrust attorney with 
the Washington law firm of Foley &AMP; Lardner. 
</P>
<P>
	``In a matter like this, the antitrust division of the Justice  
Department may view this transaction as potentially procompetitive 
in many respects,'' Burka said. 
</P>
<P>
	Spokesmen for the Justice Department and the FCC did not return  
phone calls. Many government offices in Washington were closed 
Friday to make way for NATO's 50th anniversary. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T's bid drew a lukewarm response from key U.S. senators.  
</P>
<P>
	``This proposed purchase of MediaOne Group by AT&AMP;T is a big roll  
of the dice for consumers,'' said Republican Senator Mike DeWine, 
chairman of the Senate subcommittee on antitrust, business rights 
and competition, and Democratic senator Herb Kohl, D-Wi., ranking 
member of the subcommittee, in a joint statement. 
</P>
<P>
	While the proposal could increase local telephone compeition, it  
also raises questions about whether AT&AMP;T would be too powerful, 
they said. 
</P>
<P>
	Opposition to the AT&AMP;T offer also emerged from U S West, a  
regional phone monopoly that would face new competition from AT&AMP;T. 
U S West protested AT&AMP;T's dominance of cable television lines. 
</P>
<P>
	America Online, the nation's largest provider of Internet  
access, is also likely to protest the deal. AOL and other Internet 
services have so far been unsuccessful in convincing the government 
to force AT&AMP;T to grant them broad access to its cable subscribers 
as potential customers. 
</P>
<P>
	An AOL spokesman had no comment Friday.  

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
