<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Stock Markets Close Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian stock markets ended the week higher  
Friday, boosted by another record rally overnight on Wall Street. 
</P>
<P>
	Tokyo's benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 257.37  
points, or 1.54 percent, to close at 16,923.25. On Thursday, the 
average gained 170.86 points, or 1.04 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors bought shares encouraged by overnight gains in New  
York stocks after a higher-than-expected profit report by computer 
giant International Business Machines. IBM said it had posted a 42 
percent gain in first-quarter profits and across-the-board growth 
in revenues. 
</P>
<P>
	Thursday in New York, the Dow Jones industrial average climbed  
145.76 points, or 1.37 percent, closing at 10,727.18, a record 
high. 
</P>
<P>
	Also supporting the Japanese market were hopes for more  
government stimulus measures, sparked by a newspaper report that 
Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi would disclose a plan to put together a 
new package of economic measures in his meeting with U.S. President 
Bill Clinton early in May. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the U.S. dollar was quoted at 119.58 yen at late  
afternoon, down 0.38 yen from late Thursday in Tokyo but above its 
late New York level of 119.55 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	Share prices in Hong Kong closed slightly lower Friday after two  
straight days of sharp gains. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hang Seng Index, the Hong Kong market's key indicator of  
blue chips, slipped 28.24 points, or 0.2 percent, closing at 
12,905.30. On Thursday, the index had surged 389.78 points, or 3.1 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Brokers said the index rose more than 400 points in early  
trading in reaction to record gains on Wall Street. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hang Seng Index reversed course in the afternoon as  
investors took profits. Despite Friday's decline, the index has 
gained 18 percent so far this month. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Share prices closed higher as investors renewed their  
buying spree in the wake of gains on Wall Street. The market's key 
Weighted Stock Price Index rose 118.20 points or 1.6 percent to 
7,612.80. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand share prices closed slightly higher. The  
benchmark NZSE-40 Capital Index rose 6.19 points, or 0.2 percent, 
to 2,231.30. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Philippine shares closed higher on broad interest in key  
stocks. The 30-company Philippine Stock Exchange Index rose 46.06 
points, or 1.9 percent, to 2,384.47. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: The Australian share market closed at a record high, but  
the overall gain was minor as investors chose to consolidate 
Thursday's rally. The All Ordinaries Index rose 3.4 points, or 0.1 
percent, to 3,121. 
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: Share prices closed higher, boosted by strong gains in  
overseas markets. The Korea Composite Stock Price Index rose 10.59 
points, or 1.5 percent, to 750.99. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Malaysian shares closed higher on optimism over  
the country's economic recovery. The Composite Index, which tracks 
100 blue-chip stocks, rose 10.49 points, or 1.7 percent, to 646.92. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Share prices closed little changed. The Straits Times  
Index rose 2.89 points, or 0.15 percent, to 1,865.28. 
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Indonesian share prices closed lower on profit-taking.  
The Composite Index fell 5.655 points, or 1.1 percent, to 473.587. 
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Thai stock prices closed lower as local retailers sold  
shares to take profit before the weekend. The Stock Exchange of 
Thailand index slipped 1.26 points, or 0.3 percent, to 401.07. 

</P>
</TEXT>
