<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NHL Playoffs Roundup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	As expected, the Detroit Red Wings and Dallas Stars are looking  
pretty good in the Stanley Cup playoffs. The Buffalo Sabres are 
looking even better. 
</P>
<P>
	All three teams won the first two games of their first-round  
series, but the Sabres are taking their 2-0 lead back home 
following Friday night's 3-2 double-overtime victory at Ottawa. 
</P>
<P>
	``Coming out of here with a split would have been great for  
us,'' Buffalo's Jason Woolley said. ``But after winning that first 
game without really playing as well as we can gave us hope.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Wings, meanwhile, pounded Anaheim 5-1 and the Stars beat  
Edmonton 3-2 before going on the road against their lower-seeded 
opponents. 
</P>
<P>
	The playoffs continued today with Pittsburgh at New Jersey and  
St. Louis at Phoenix. Tonight, it's Boston at Carolina, 
Philadelphia at Toronto and Colorado at San Jose. New Jersey, St. 
Louis, Boston and Philadelphia all lead their series 1-0. 
</P>
<P>
	The Colorado-San Jose series is opening late because of the  
shooting deaths at a suburban Denver high school. 
</P>
<P>
	Miroslav Satan scored his second goal of the game at 10:35 of  
the second overtime period to give the Sabres a victory over the 
favored Senators, who finished second in the Eastern Conference and 
were 12 points better than Buffalo. 
</P>
<P>
	After a turnover in the neutral zone, Woolley took a shot that  
Damian Rhodes kicked out with his left pad. The rebound came out to 
Satan, who slapped it into the empty net. 
</P>
<P>
	The series shifts to Buffalo for Game 3 on Sunday and Game 4 on  
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We felt (Friday night's victory) was just a matter of time,''  
Buffalo's Joe Juneau said. ``We were really confident and we made 
sure nobody thought otherwise. Obviously, it's a great advantage 
going home up 2-0 with a chance to make it 3-0. I don't know what 
will happen, but we'd love to win it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For the second time in the series, Buffalo goalie Dominik Hasek  
played a big role for the Sabres. He made 40 stops in Wednesday 
night's 2-1 victory, and stopped 45 on Friday night, giving up 85 
saves on 88 shots in the two games. 
</P>
<P>
                      *Red Wings 5, Mighty Ducks 1    	
</P>
<P>
	Brendan Shanahan had two goals and an assist for Detroit against  
Anaheim. 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Wings, who swept the first two games of only one series  
last season en route to their second straight Stanley Cup, head to 
Anaheim for Game 3 on Sunday. The Ducks have only been in two 
playoff series before, winning one, and have never overcome a 2-0 
deficit. 
</P>
<P>
	Sergei Fedorov had two assists for the second straight game, and  
Tomas Holmstrom, Doug Brown and Steve Yzerman, who had three goals 
Wednesday, added a goal each. Teemu Selanne scored for Anaheim. 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Wings were 3-of-9 on the power play, while the Ducks,  
who had the top power-play unit in the NHL this season with a 25.5 
percent success rate, were 1-of-4. 
</P>
<P>
                          *Stars 3, Oilers 2    	
</P>
<P>
	Jere Lehtinen and Guy Carbonneau both scored for the second game  
in a row for Dallas. 
</P>
<P>
	Jamie Langenbrunnner scored the game-winner with his first goal  
of the playoffs. His goal at 14:22 of the third period made it 3-1 
before Edmonton's Doug Weight scored with 3:11 left to make it a 
one-goal game again. 
</P>
<P>
	Both goalies were strong, as Edmonton's Tommy Salo stopped 31  
shots and Dallas' Ed Belfour turned back 17. Dallas outshot the 
Oilers 34-19. 
</P>
</TEXT>
