<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Oilers Down Two but Buoyed by Home / Hockey Game Story  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EDMONTON, Alberta (AP) -- Down two games to none and outshot by a  
margin of 2-1, the only thing the Edmonton Oilers have going for 
them is home ice -- literally. 
</P>
<P>
	The Oilers got bogged down on the humid, mushy ice at Dallas'  
Reunion Arena in the first two games of the NHL Western Conference 
quarterfinal series. 
</P>
<P>
	The Stars used the ice to their advantage, earning a 2-0 lead  
with a punishing, trapping style of play that allowed just 13 shots 
on goalie Ed Belfour in the first game and 19 in the second. 
</P>
<P>
	``Their game plan is not going to change much,'' Edmonton coach  
Ron Low said Saturday. ``They're going to try and keep it as tight 
as possible in the neutral zone and we'll have to find ways through 
that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Oilers are a young, fast-skating, hard-hitting team and  
figure a long series of quick strides and board-bending hits is 
their only chance of beating the Stars, who have 14 players over 
30. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll be able to make a lot more passes and do different  
things we couldn't do down there,'' Oilers defenseman Tom Poti 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The ice here doesn't wear down as much as it does in Dallas.  
It was like trying to stickhandle on grass (there). It's just 
impossible to play on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Forward Doug Weight added: ``You've got 20 minutes (in a period)  
to make passes here where you have about an eight-minute window 
there'' before the ice turns to slush. 
</P>
<P>
	Dallas's blue-line corps, led by Richard Matvichuk and Sergei  
Zubov, has allowed few rebounds, few bodies in front of the net and 
has blocked a ton of shots. 
</P>
<P>
	``They block 10, 15, 20 shots a game,'' Oilers forward Todd  
Marchant said. ``We've got to get those shots through and get the 
rebounds.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Weight agreed. ``They get into your head a bit with their  
blocked shots. You see three or four in the first couple of shifts, 
then guys try to make extra moves and passes to the middle, which 
they want us to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Oilers goal drought continued in Game 2 even though their  
two top scorers, Bill Guerin and Josef Beranek, returned from knee 
injuries. They've lost by 2-1 and 3-2 scores. 
</P>
<P>
	Low said the Oilers game plan remains hit and hit often. The  
Oilers have 129 hits over two games compared with 81 by Dallas, 
about the only statistical category in which the Oilers have an 
edge. 
</P>
<P>
	The Stars have been playing like seasoned playoff veterans. They  
have controlled the tempo in both games from start to finish. The 
only concern has been their power play, which is 0-for-10. 
</P>
<P>
	The Oilers, an inconsistent team all season, now face the task  
of beating the NHL's best team four times in five games to extend 
the season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
