<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Patience Game Wins Derby Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- Patience Game, making his stakes debut in  
only his fourth start, wrested the lead from Yes It's True and 
Straight Man at the top of the stretch and won the Derby Trial on 
opening day Saturday at Churchill Downs. 
</P>
<P>
	The three 3-year-old colts hit the quarter pole almost as one.  
Then Patience Game, ridden by Corey Nakatani, opened a daylight 
lead and went on to win by 2 1/4 lengths over Prime Directive, who 
closed to take the place by 2 3/4 lengths over Straight Man. 
</P>
<P>
	Yes It's True finished another half-length back in the  
nine-horse field. 
</P>
<P>
	None of the nine are set to compete in the 125th Kentucky Derby  
next Saturday. Plans called for Patience Game, trained by Alex 
Hassinger Jr., to run in the Illinois Derby on May 8 at Sportsman's 
Park or in the Preakness on May 15 at Pimlico. 
</P>
<P>
	Patience Game carried 114 pounds, eight pounds less than Prime  
Directive, over one mile in 1:37.86 and paid $9, $4.60 and $3.40 to 
his backers in a crowd of 17,323 on a cool, sunny day. 
</P>
<P>
	The winner earned $71,176 from a purse of $114,800 for his  
owner, Prince Ahmed Salman of Saudi Arabia, who will try to win the 
Derby with Desert Hero. 
</P>
<P>
	In his three races before the Trial, all this year, Patience  
Game finished second in two maiden races at Santa Anita, then broke 
his maiden in a mile race March 27 at that track. 
</P>
<P>
	Prime Directive, ridden by Pat Day, returned $6.60 and $4.  
Straight Man (122) was worth $3.80 to show. He was ridden by David 
Flores and is trained by Bob Baffert, who will saddle General 
Challenge and Prime Timber in a bid for an unprecedented third 
straight victory in the Kentucky Derby. 
</P>
<P>
	Completing the order of finish were Lead Em Home, Kutsa,  
Donerail Court, Hector and Nebrasska. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990424.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 01:51:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Nomo Released by Cubs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- With four pitchers on the disabled list,  
including Kerry Wood who is out for the season, the Chicago Cubs 
might have adopted a what-have-we-got-to-lose philosophy with Hideo 
Nomo. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, when Nomo refused to make two more starts in the minors  
on top of the three he's already had with their Triple-A farm club, 
the Cubs released the former NL rookie of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was our opinion he was not ready to join our major league  
club,'' Cubs general manager Ed Lynch said Friday, one day after 
Nomo was wild in his third start at Class AAA Iowa. 
</P>
<P>
	Under an agreement with the Cubs, Nomo was to make three starts  
for Iowa and then Chicago would either promote him to the majors 
with an $800,000 base salary plus incentives that could total 
another $2 million, ask him to stay longer in the minors or release 
him. 
</P>
<P>
	Lynch asked Nomo's agent, Don Nomura, if his client would agree  
to two more starts at Iowa. Nomura said no and so the Cubs released 
him. 
</P>
<P>
	``He really didn't seem interested in any additional time in  
Triple-A,'' Lynch said. 
</P>
<P>
	In Nomo's third start with Iowa on Thursday, he walked six,  
struck out five and gave up three hits and two runs in six innings 
during a 3-1 loss to Memphis. He threw 51 strikes and 47 balls. 
</P>
<P>
	``We looked at the quality of his pitches and command,'' said  
Lynch, a former major league pitcher. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you have someone who has either very good command or  
overpowering stuff, one of the two, you could justify bringing him 
to your major league club. We just didn't see the command or stuff 
that we felt was good enough to get major league hitters out. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's our opinion. I'm sure he has a different opinion of his  
command and his stuff.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nomo and Nomura were not available for comment.  
</P>
<P>
	Nomo was waived by the New York Mets this spring and the Cubs,  
hungry for pitching with Wood out for the season following elbow 
surgery, signed Nomo to a Triple-A deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Starters Kevin Tapani and Jeremi Gonzalez and reliever Terry  
Adams are also on the DL. 
</P>
<P>
	Lynch said he was disappointed that it didn't work out with  
Nomo, acknowledging that he might be ready for a return to the 
majors by summer. He said he expected Nomo to re-enter the free 
agent market. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would have been a nice boost to add a pitcher of his name  
to our staff,'' Lynch said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think it was fair to our club right now to bring him  
to the major leagues.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nomo's previous two outings at Iowa were more encouraging than  
his third. He allowed five earned runs in 11 innings. In his second 
appearance against Las Vegas, he pitched six shutout innings and 
struck out 10. 
</P>
<P>
	In his three Triple-A starts, he was 1-1 with a 3.71 ERA,  
striking out 18 and walking 12 while allowing 12 hits and seven 
runs in 17 innings. 
</P>
<P>
	Nomo's major league record is 49-41 with a 3.66 ERA in four  
seasons with the Los Angeles Dodgers and Mets, but he faltered last 
season. He went 6-12 with a 4.92 ERA last year with the Dodgers and 
Mets. 
</P>
<P>
	He was ineffective this spring, going 0-2 with a 7.62 ERA in  
four appearances, before the Mets gave up on him. They sent him to 
Triple-A Norfolk outright March 24 and put him on unconditional 
release waivers two days later. 
</P>
<P>
	Nomo was the NL's Rookie of the Year in 1995 when he struck out  
236 and allowed hitters just a .182 average. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
