<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Colo. Sheriff: Parents Share Blame  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLETON, Colo. (AP) -- The local sheriff said today that he  
believes the parents of two gunmen who went on a shooting spree at 
Columbine High School should ``be accountable'' for their kids' 
actions after authorities found a diary, shotgun barrel and 
bomb-making materials inside one of the boys' bedroom. ``A lot of 
this stuff was clearly visible and the parents should have known,'' 
Jefferson County Sheriff John Stone. ``I think parents should be 
accountable for their kid's actions.'' The parents have not 
commented beyond separate written statements released by their 
attorneys. The statements expressed sorrow and sympathy for the 
victims' families. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Pushes Violence Prevention  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton will ask Congress for money  
and stricter gun laws to help stem school violence such as the 
attack last week at a Colorado high school in which 15 people were 
killed. Clinton said in his weekly radio address today that he 
wants to keep guns away from juveniles and will seek $12 million 
for emergency teams ``to help communities respond when tragedy 
strikes.'' The attack in Littleton, Colo., was the seventh at 
schools around the country in two years. 

</P>
<P>
	Thousands Protest Attack on Serb TV  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Thousands of Belgrade residents  
marched today to a church near the bomb-shattered headquarters of 
Serb TV, protesting a NATO attack that authorities say killed 15 
people and injured 30. From the march route, search crews could be 
seen digging through the jumble of concrete and steel where 
missiles struck early yesterday in what NATO called an attack on 
the Serbian government's ``propaganda machine.'' NATO staged more 
attacks tonight, causing heavy damage in regions southeast and 
southwest of Belgrade, according to the Yugoslav news agency 
Tanjug. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Want To Cut Serb's Oil  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- NATO ran into defiant objections from Russia  
and questions from its own members today about enforcing an oil 
embargo against Yugoslavia by searching ships at sea. On the second 
day of their summit, NATO leaders said military commanders were 
laying plans under orders issued last night for sea searches to 
``switch off the oil tap'' fueling Yugoslav President Slobodan 
Milosevic's military machine. But Russia, angry about 32 days of 
airstrikes against Yugoslavia, indicated it would ignore an 
embargo. 

</P>
<P>
	Forbes Pushes Abortion Ban  
</P>
<P>
	NEWARK, Calif. (AP) -- Republican presidential hopeful Steve  
Forbes urged conservative activists today to lay the groundwork for 
banning abortions by turning public opinion against the procedure. 
Forbes favors a constitutional ``human life'' amendment to outlaw 
abortions. But he acknowledged in a speech that ``many people do 
not yet agree with our ultimate goal -- a life amendment.'' Forbes 
was the second of five GOP White House hopefuls to address the 
conservative CRA, which will endorse a candidate in November and by 
doing so mobilize thousands of its activists. 

</P>
<P>
	Munnings Painting Fetches $739,500  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A watercolor by Alfred J. Munnings, which once  
graced the walls of a Manhattan apartment belonging to socialite 
Betsey Cushing Whitney and her husband, set an auction record for 
the artist today at Sotheby's. Munnings' ``Violent Munnings' Horse 
`Chips' at Chantilly,'' a portrait of a racehorse belonging to the 
artist's wife, fetched $739,500, setting a new auction record price 
for a Munnings watercolor. The previous record was $122,173 for 
Munnings' ``A Little Piece of England,'' sold in November 1997. 

</P>
<P>
	Hornets Beat Nets  
</P>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- David Wesley had 19 points and nine  
assists as the Charlotte Hornets kept pace in their pursuit of a 
playoff berth with a 97-82 victory over the New Jersey Nets 
tonight. Elden Campbell had 16 points and 13 rebounds for the 
Hornets, who moved into a three-way tie with Toronto and New York 
for the eighth and final Eastern Conference playoff spot. Derrick 
Coleman added 16 points and nine rebounds, while Bobby Phills and 
Chucky Brown each had 14 points for the Hornets. 

</P>
<P>
	Rangers 7, Twins 2  
</P>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Mike Morgan gave Texas its third consecutive  
solid pitching performance, and Juan Gonzalez drove in three runs 
for the second straight game as the Rangers beat the Minnesota 
Twins 7-2 tonight. Morgan (4-0), with his major league record 11th 
team, gave up seven hits and two runs in seven innings for the best 
start of his career. His four victories, including one in relief, 
top the major leagues. 


</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS  
</P>
