<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cable-Car Charges Remain for Pilot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. (AP) -- A military trial will proceed next  
week to determine whether a Marine pilot obstructed justice after 
his jet clipped an Italian gondola cable, killing 20 people. 
</P>
<P>
	A judge refused Friday to dismiss the obstruction charges  
against Capt. Richard Ashby, 32, of Mission Viejo, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge, Col. Alvin Keller, rejected arguments by Ashby's  
lawyers that high-ranking Marine officers improperly influenced the 
decision to prosecute Ashby. 
</P>
<P>
	During a low-level training mission on Feb. 3, 1998, Ashby's  
four-man EA-6B Prowler jet severed the gondola cable in the Italian 
Alps, and 20 people plunged to their deaths. He was acquitted of 
manslaughter charges in March. 
</P>
<P>
	In the obstruction case, Ashby is accused of destroying a  
videotape shot during the flight. 
</P>
<P>
	Ashby testified during his manslaughter trial that he removed  
the tape after the flight and handed it to his navigator, Capt. 
Joseph Schweitzer, 31, of Westbury, N.Y. Schweitzer said he threw 
the tape into a bonfire, fearing images of him smiling into the 
camera would be shown on Italian television. 
</P>
<P>
	``The facts will show that Captain Ashby ultimately returned the  
tape to the person who owned the tape,'' Ashby's attorney, Frank 
Spinner, said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Schweitzer pleaded guilty earlier this month to obstruction of  
justice and conspiracy charges. The judge recommended his dismissal 
from the Marines. 
</P>
<P>
	Jury selection in Ashby's trial is to start Monday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
