<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Francis Out of Carolina Lineup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREENSBORO, N.C. (AP) -- Carolina's Ron Francis, the hottest  
scorer for the Hurricanes in the second half of the season, tested 
his sprained ankle Saturday but was unable to play in Game 2 
against Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	Francis, 36, appeared in all 82 regular-season game for Carolina  
and scored 36 points over his final 41 games. But the center was 
held out of the playoff game against the Bruins after injuring his 
right ankle in Game 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Francis suffered the injury in the first period of Boston's 2-0  
victory over Carolina on Thursday night when Bruins defenseman 
Steve Heinze fell on him behind the net. 
</P>
<P>
	X-rays were negative later than night. But the 18-year NHL  
veteran who won two Stanley Cups for Pittsburgh in the early 1990s, 
said the ankle was just too tender to go in Saturday night's 
Eastern Conference playoff game. 
</P>
<P>
	Francis said he tested the ankle twice before the game, but came  
to the conclusion he couldn't help the team. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are certain areas where I can't do what you need to do  
on the ice,'' said Francis, who led the team in minutes played and 
power play points. 
</P>
<P>
	Francis said he didn't feel very good in his first test on the  
ice at the Greensboro Coliseum about 2 1/2 hours before game time, 
then tried it again minutes later with more support in his boot. 
</P>
<P>
	``In this business you are competitive by nature and you want to  
try different ways to see if you can't make it work. We tried 
something else and it just didn't happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Francis will be replaced in the Carolina lineup by Robert Kron,  
who was a healthy scratch for Game 1 and scored only nine goals in 
75 games this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Francis said he didn't address the team prior to the game.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to be a distraction or a sideshow at this  
point,'' he said. ``I decided to test it early so it wouldn't 
happen right here (in front of everybody).'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's still unclear if the ankle will be ready for Game 3 in  
Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wish I could say 100 percent one way or the other, but I  
really don't know. Does it feel better today than it did two night 
ago? Yeah. Does that mean it will be good enough by Monday? 
Hopefully, but I can't say that with any certainty.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
