<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 13:52:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Leaders Enjoying Plush Hotels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- NATO Secretary General Javier Solana sleeps in  
a plush six-room suite with crystal chandeliers and furnishings 
just a shade lighter than ``NATO blue.'' Romanian President Emil 
Constantinescu strolls across marble to enter his regal 
red-and-gold hotel room. French President Jacques Chirac's suite 
has a oval dining room and four bathrooms. 
</P>
<P>
	Foreign leaders at NATO's 50th anniversary are staying in more  
than a dozen of Washington's fanciest hotels. 
</P>
<P>
	The 143 sleeping rooms at the Hay-Adams Hotel were booked solid  
a year ago by three foreign delegations. Spokeswoman Jennifer 
Girgus wouldn't identify the VIPs, but said multi-lingual ``lobby 
ambassadors'' are helping guests find anything from a photocopy 
machine to a city landmark. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales managers fluent in Arabic, German, French and Italian also  
mill through the lobby of the Hotel Washington from 6 a.m. to 8 
p.m. to assist foreign guests staying in more than 100 of its 355 
rooms. ``The sales managers just happen to know the languages and 
so it was a very good plus for us,'' said manager Walid Harb. 
</P>
<P>
	While foreign visitors are being treated like royalty, hotel  
managers say they've tried to temper their hospitality. Parties are 
taboo because of the NATO bombing campaign in Yugoslavia and the 
plight of hundreds of thousands of Kosovars. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're trying to honor the historic occasion without being  
excessive in light of the events in Yugoslavia,'' said Kristina 
Messner, spokeswoman for the Willard Inter-Continental Hotel. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the hotel had gifts waiting for Solana, Chirac and  
Constantinescu: two replicas of the Capitol -- one in crystal that's 
about the size of a paperweight and another in chocolate. 
</P>
<P>
	``The chocolate Capitol dome was 8 to 10 inches high,'' she  
said. ``It was on a pastry display surrounded by petit fours and a 
variety of French pastries.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Like a gaggle of unsure ducklings, 20 world leaders on their way  
to lunch Saturday followed a path that NATO summit organizers had 
paved with red carpets laid at angles: out toward a riser of news 
cameras, hard left turn, straight line across a courtyard, another 
left, and back into the International Trade Center. 
</P>
<P>
	It was plotted for maximum ``photo-op.'' And so, at dead center,  
President Clinton halted the cluster and tried to get everyone to 
more or less spread out and face the cameras. 
</P>
<P>
	Polish President Aleksander Kwasniewski pointed to the carpet  
yet ahead and asked: ``But aren't we supposed to walk that way?'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	What to buy for America's foreign friends?  
</P>
<P>
	Silver, porcelain and crystal, according to the White House  
press office. 
</P>
<P>
	To: NATO leaders -- a medallion, made by Tiffany &AMP; Co.,  
commemorating the 50th anniversary of the alliance and white 
porcelain bowls decorated with the flags of NATO countries. 
</P>
<P>
	To: Leaders of NATO partner countries -- a crystal bridge  
sculpture titled ``Partnership'' set on a granite base. 
</P>
<P>
	Their spouses received white porcelain plates decorated with the  
flags, sterling silver compacts or hand-painted porcelain boxes of 
the White House or vice president's residence. 
</P>
<P>
	Foreign ministers, defense ministers and members of their  
delegations received crystal globes, 3 inches in diameter, cherry 
stationery boxes with commemorative coins or pewter desk boxes 
decorated with flags of member nations. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Flag bearers have a hectic job shuffling the national banners of  
the various countries when NATO dignitaries arrive for dinner at 
the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	Official cars cruise up the drive of the executive mansion.  
White-gloved military men open the doors. The first thing the 
foreign officials see is their country's flag and Old Glory. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will be a challenge when the motorcades come,'' says Thomas  
Groppel, director of ceremonies and special events for the Military 
District of Washington, which is responsible for Army activities in 
the nation's capital. 
</P>
<P>
	With only a few minutes of notice, flag workers must identify  
the arriving guest -- not an easy job with more than 40 foreign 
leaders zigzagging around Washington. Then, they have to grab the 
proper national flag, making sure, for example, not to mistake 
Luxembourg's red-white-and-LIGHT blue flag for the Netherlands' 
red-white-and-DARK blue one. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will have to be quick,'' Groppel says. ``We have to decide  
who it is, which flag is his and get it in place before he gets 
there.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
