<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Obituraries in the News    	
</P>
<P>
                         *Gerald V. Caldwell    	
</P>
<P>
	FRANKLIN, Neb. (AP) -- Gerald V. ``Jerry'' Caldwell, the former  
mayor and postmaster of Campbell and publisher of the Campbell 
News, died Wednesday. He was 76. 
</P>
<P>
	A Colorado native, Caldell grew up in Fremont and Omaha. He  
served in the Army during World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	Caldwell and his wife, Opal, owned and published the Campbell  
News from 1949-73. 
</P>
<P>
	He was postmaster from 1964 until his retirement in 1983. He  
also served as Campbell's mayor and police magistrate. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include a son and daughter, a sister, two  
half-sisters, three grandchildren and 3 great-grandchildren. 

</P>
<P>
 *Konrad Henkel    	
</P>
<P>
	DUESSELDORF, Germany (AP) -- German industrialist Konrad Henkel,  
who for five decades oversaw the expansion of his grandfather's 
soap business into a worldwide chemical concern, died Saturday at 
age 83. 
</P>
<P>
	The Henkel Group is the maker of some of Europe's best known  
soap and cosmetic products, including Persil laundry detergent and 
Schwarzkopf hair products. 
</P>
<P>
	Henkel's grandfather, Fritz, founded the business in 1876.  
Henkel took it over in 1961 after the death of his brother Jost, 
and worked to establish the company worldwide. Currently, Henkel 
employs 56,300 people in 70 countries. 
</P>
<P>
	A trained chemist, Henkel worked first as a researcher before  
going to work at the family business in 1948. 
</P>
<P>
	While pushing the company's expansion, Henkel encouraged  
research on ways to make its products more environmentally safe. 
Under his leadership, the company created substitutes for 
phosphates in its laundry detergent. 
</P>
<P>
	Henkel stepped down in 1980, and the company went public in  
1985. He was named honorary chairman in 1990. 

</P>
<P>
 *Sir Laurence Kirwan    	
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Sir Laurence Kirwan, who led the Royal Geographic  
Society for three decades and helped organize the first conquest of 
Mt. Everest, died April 16. He was 91. 
</P>
<P>
	As director and secretary of the society from 1945 to 1975,  
Kirwan was deeply involved in organizing three major expeditions: 
the Norwegian-British-Swedish Antarctic expedition of 1949-52 led 
by John Giaever; the 1953 Everest expedition led by John Hunt; and 
the trans-Antarctic expedition of 1955-57 led by Vivian Fuchs. 
</P>
<P>
	Leaving Oxford University without a degree, Kirwan spent a  
season in Egypt working for the British Museum. In 1929, he was 
appointed assistant director of the Egyptian government's 
archaeological survey of Nubia. 
</P>
<P>
	From 1934 to 1937, Kirwan was field director of Oxford  
University expeditions to the Sudan, carrying out excavations of 
the royal tombs of the 4th and 5th centuries A.D. at Ballana and 
Qustal. From 1937 to 1939 he continued extensive fieldwork as 
Tweedie Fellow in Archaeology and Anthropology at Edinburgh 
University. 
</P>
<P>
	Kirwan was co-author, with W.B. Emery, of ``Excavations and  
Survey between Wadi-es-Sebua and Adindan,'' published in 1935, 
detailing the survey's work. 
</P>
<P>
	He and Emery teamed again to write ``Oxford University  
Excavations at Firka'' in 1938, which also led to Kirwan gaining at 
master's degree in literature from Oxford. 
</P>
<P>
	Kirwan's association with the two Antarctic expeditions inspired  
his book, ``The White Road,'' published in 1959, which surveyed the 
history of polar exploration. 
</P>
<P>
	Although he retired as director and secretary of the Royal  
Geographical Society in 1975, he continued to edit the Geographic 
Journal for three more years. 
</P>
<P>
	Kirwan was knighted in 1972, and received the Knight Cross of  
the Order of St. Olav from Norway in 1975. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Shirley Ware    	
</P>
<P>
	OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Shirley Ware, a nurse who later became a  
health care union leader, died Friday of cancer. She was 57. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1971, Ware joined Health Care Workers Union/SEIU Local 250 as  
the first black female representative since the union formed in 
1934 at San Francisco General Hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	Under her leadership, the union grew by 20,000 members. Its  
46,000 members makes it the nation's second-large health care local 
union behind a counterpart chapter in New York City. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
