<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 00:41:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stars Come Out at Penn Relays </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- With its biggest live audience on hand,  
headliners Marion Jones and Michael Johnson are ready to take 
center stage at the Penn Relays. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, Jones and the rest of their Nike teammates plan to hit  
the track today, the final day of the 105th running of the meet. 
</P>
<P>
	A crowd of 31,904 braved cold temperatures and thunderstorms  
Friday and sat through delays that hadn't occurred in decades. 
</P>
<P>
	The meet was delayed by lightning, but resumed after a 20-minute  
stoppage. Competition continued for 30 minutes, but had to be 
halted again for 1:20. After another restart, competition continued 
for 1:15. 
</P>
<P>
	The remainder of the program, including the men's and women's  
sprint medley relay finals, was postponed until today. 
</P>
<P>
	The Penn Relays, the best-attended meet in the United States,  
was expected to draw upwards of 40,000 for its final day of 
competition. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not too often as American athletes, we can stay home and  
go to a track meet,'' Jones said. ``We love to compete in front of 
all the people, and the Penn Relays is definitely a highlight for 
me and I'm sure probably for all of us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, who briefly ignited interest in track and field here at  
home when he starred during the 1996 Atlanta Olympics, shared the 
sentiment on this storied meet. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's the greatest track meet in America,'' said  
Johnson, who was scheduled to run with another world champion, 
Maurice Greene, in today's 800-meter relay. ``It's always just a 
great crowd, a knowledgeable crowd about track and field. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just fun to be able to walk into a stadium here in  
America for a track meet and see that many people in the stands. 
It's a great feeling.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In results from Friday's relays, Seneca Lassiter, the most  
valuable male track athlete in the 1997 Penn Relays, who was 
severely hampered last year by illness and allergies, anchored 
Arkansas to victory in the distance medley relay. 
</P>
<P>
	The victory was Arkansas' seventh in the distance medley relay  
during the 1990s and its 13th in 16 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Wisconsin, led by Janet Westphal, repeated as women's  
6,000-meter relay champion at 17:37.15, beating BYU by 15 meters. 
</P>
<P>
	Tennessee, which has won the most men's 440 shuttle hurdles  
relays, added its 11th title at 56.35, while LSU's women won their 
third 400 shuttle hurdles relay championship, the first since 1992, 
at 54.91. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas ended LSU's four-year winning streak in the women's 400  
relay and won the event for the first time since 1989 at 43.33, 
setting Penn Relays and Franklin Field records. The previous record 
for both was 43.42 by LSU last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Longhorns' foursome of Kim McGruder, Nanceen Perry, LaKiesha  
White and LaKeisha Backus beat LSU by nearly a second at 44.27. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones, the world No. 1 in the 100- and 200-meter races and in  
the long jump, was scheduled to run with Inger Miller, Gail Devers 
and Susanthika Jayasinghe in today's 400-meter Olympic Development 
relay and with Miller, Jayasinghe and Falilat Ogunkoya in the 800. 
</P>
<P>
	Another world champion Maurice Greene, was scheduled to run in  
the Olympic Development 400 and join Johnson to make up half of the 
Nike entry in the 800. 
</P>
<P>
	According to Greene, although the top runners come from the  
United States, there aren't enough chances to show the home folks 
how good they are. 
</P>
<P>
	``Give us the stages to run, and let us do our jobs,'' he said.  
``If they give us places to run and put out what we need to have a 
good meet, we'll do our jobs. It's up to us to bring in the fan 
base.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was announced Thursday at the opening of the Penn Relays that  
Johnson, who became a household name at the Atlanta Olympics, will 
be a principal attraction in the new Track and Field Association, a 
professional circuit that hopes to improve fan interest in the 
United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The group will debut in June with the TFA Pro Championships in  
Uniondale, N.Y., the site of the track and field competition at 
last year's Goodwill Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Even with a new venture on the horizon, Johnson and his fellow  
competitors recognize what the tradition of the Penn Relays means 
to the sport. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have people who have planned their schedules in the spring  
around the Penn Relays, so it's very important,'' Johnson said. 
``It's a very significant stop on the American circuit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The popularity of track around the world makes these stars more  
famous elsewhere, compared to at home where they can go virtually 
unrecognized. 
</P>
<P>
	``The more we're seen, the more we're known,'' Greene said.  
``We're seen all the time in Europe, that's why we're so well 
known.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If American fans could be enticed to come out, the performers  
are ready to deliver a top product. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it weren't for the fans, there wouldn't be any need for  
us,'' Greene said. ``We go out there and do our jobs, but the fans 
make it that much easier. The fans here at the Penn Relays are just 
great.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
