<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Students Pay Homage to Dead Teen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLETON, Colo. (AP) -- In stocking feet, teen-ager after  
teen-ager entered Cassie Bernall's bedroom, glimpsing pieces of a 
life cut short. 
</P>
<P>
	Blue sparkly nail polish. Black woolen clogs. Pictures of  
kittens. Clothes on the floor. A love poem on the wall. A teacher's 
note, ``I cannot see how you missed the purpose of the assignment 
completely.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The mourners were a busload of friends from the 17-year-old's  
church youth group. In all, 40 teen-agers went late Friday to pay 
their respects to her family. 
</P>
<P>
	Twelve of the visiting students were at Columbine when the  
shootings took place. They had been forced to flee, stepping over 
bodies to escape, or hide in closets. Their friend Cassie was among 
those who didn't make it out alive. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's in good hands,'' said one girl, breaking the silence,  
after stooping to examine photos on the carpet. 
</P>
<P>
	On the bus, members of the group looked and acted like typical  
teen-agers. After the visit, some threw snowballs at the church's 
donated, pale military green bus parked down the street. Teen-agers 
inside shrieked and taunted them. 
</P>
<P>
	But before they approached the house, some held hands and  
slapped shoulders. Some hugged. Others were bleary from crying. As 
they entered, the 40 took off their shoes so they wouldn't track 
snow from that day's storm through the house. 
</P>
<P>
	Some closed their eyes and mouthed the words to Christian music  
that blared over the roar of the bus. Some shed tears. 
</P>
<P>
	The bus driver, group leader and pastor David McPherson, said:  
``Death is not our friend, but it is our companion. It's always 
hanging around.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
