<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wash. Post, Oregonian, ABC Honored </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Washington Post, The Oregonian, and ABC News  
each won two awards for outstanding achievement in foreign 
reporting. The Associated Press was honored as well. 
</P>
<P>
	AP reporters Ken Guggenheim and Niko Price took the Overseas  
Press Club of America's award for newspaper or wire service 
reporting from abroad for their coverage of Hurricane Mitch. 
</P>
<P>
	Barton Gellman of the Post was selected for best newspaper or  
wire service interpretation of foreign affairs for his work on the 
search for Iraq's hidden weapons. The newspaper's Kevin Sullivan, 
Mary Jordan and Keith Richburg won for best foreign reporting 
``showing a concern for the human condition.'' The three worked 
together on ``Shattered Lives: The Asian Middle Class.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brenda Breslauer and Brian Ross of ABC News were honored for  
best business reporting for the network's report about artwork 
stolen by the Nazis. Cynthia McFadden and Beth Osisk of ABC and 
``Primetime Live'' won for a report entitled: ``Russian Girls for 
Sale.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Richard Read of The Oregonian of Portland, Ore., won for best  
newspaper or wire service business reporting. Read's story, ``The 
French Fry Connection,'' illustrated the impact of the Asian 
economic crisis by following the U.S. export of frozen french 
fries. Read's four-part series also won the 1999 Pulitzer Prize for 
explanatory reporting. 
</P>
<P>
	The Oregonian's Mark O'Keefe won for best print reporting on  
human rights for his work on ``Christians Under Siege.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Maynard Parker, editor of Newsweek magazine from 1982 until his  
death last October, was honored posthumously with the President's 
Award. 
</P>
<P>
	In all, the New York-based club on Thursday presented 19 awards  
for print, electronic and photographic achievement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
