<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lewinsky Book Tour Hits Florida </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) -- Apparently rattled by a couple of  
tough interviews, Monica Lewinsky's publicist says the former White 
House intern is done with American reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	After a grilling by Matt Lauer on NBC's ``Today'' show Friday,  
Lewinsky left the studio and canceled an interview she promised to 
ABC News Radio. 
</P>
<P>
	Jamie Brickhouse of St. Martin's Press -- the company that  
published ``Monica's Story'' and has sponsored Lewinsky's book tour 
-- later told The Washington Post that Lewinsky would complete 
appearances in Miami, New Orleans, and Dallas this week, but 
planned no more interviews in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither Lewinsky's spokesperson nor one for NBC immediately  
returned telephone messages left by The Associated Press, but 
Brickhouse told the Post that the interview with Lauer ``was very 
emotional'' for Lewinsky. 
</P>
<P>
	``She just felt like she was not prepared that they were going  
to ask those kinds of questions,'' Brickhouse said in Saturday's 
Post. 
</P>
<P>
	Lauer asked her if she understood that her affair with President  
Clinton brought the country to a halt for the past year. 
</P>
<P>
	And why, Lauer asked, if she says she doesn't want to ``make a  
career out of being Monica Lewinsky,'' did she attend the Vanity 
Fair Academy Awards party. 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, a smiling Lewinsky signed nearly 1,000 books for  
throngs of people who waited in line outside Coral Gables bookstore 
for hours. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
