<DOCNO> APW19990424.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 00:41:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Schrader Wins Talladega Pole </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TALLADEGA, Ala. (AP) -- Kenny Schrader doesn't get excited about  
winning poles. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's nice to start up front, but what we really want to do is  
finish there,'' Schrader said Friday after leading the qualifying 
for the DieHard 500 at Talladega Superspeedway. 
</P>
<P>
	Schrader now has 23 poles in his Winston Cup career, but only  
four victories -- the first of which came on this same 2.66-mile, 
high-banked track on July 31, 1988. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite that win, though, Schrader's overall record in races at  
Talladega has not been very successful, with only four other 
top-five finishes in 28 starts at NASCAR's longest and fastest 
oval. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can (win),'' Schrader said. ``There's a lot of guys that  
can. You just have to stay out of trouble all day, and that ain't 
easy at this place.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As for winning the pole with a lap of 197.765 mph, Schrader gave  
most of the credit to his crew and his Chevrolet, the same car in 
which he won the pole here last October, then qualified third and 
finished sixth in the Daytona 500 in February. 
</P>
<P>
	``The driver didn't do much today,'' he said. ``It makes a big  
difference what kind of ride you have. The guys at the shop had the 
car all geared up. It was good in practice and the guys don't put 
the whole (qualifying) package on it in practice, so we knew it 
would be close.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bobby Labonte, who won this race from the pole a year ago, was  
close behind in a Pontiac at 197.488, followed by the Ford of 
series points leader Jeff Burton at 197.252. 
</P>
<P>
	With the cars nearing 200 mph again, despite the carburetor  
restrictor plates required by NASCAR at Talladega and Daytona, 
Schrader was asked why the speeds keep increasing. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody's just done a good job of getting the cars down to  
the ground and everybody's done a good job of getting more 
horsepower,'' he said. ``They just keep making the cars slicker. 
Nobody backs up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Labonte, almost totally healed from shoulder he broke sustained  
in a crash earlier this season in Darlington, S.C., said, ``You 
just expect to be fast at Talladega. The numbers don't mean much. 
If it's 193 or 196 or 199, it's fast.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His record at Talladega is considerably better than Schrader's,  
with finishes of eighth or better in six of his last eight starts 
here. That includes his victory last spring and finishing runner-up 
to Dale Jarrett in the fall race. 
</P>
<P>
	Joe Nemechek was fourth in the opening qualifying session at  
197.187, followed by Rusty Wallace at 196.616, Mark Martin at 
196.584, Ricky Rudd at 196.362, rookie Tony Stewart at 196.346, 
Chad Little at 196.065 and, rounding out the top 10, Michael 
Waltrip at 195.989. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeff Gordon, the two-time defending Winston Cup champion, was a  
little disappointed after qualifying 13th at 195.880. 
</P>
<P>
	``The pole at Daytona and now 13th here,'' Gordon lamented.  
``We're starting further back than I'd like to. 
</P>
<P>
	``We ran about what we tested here, but we thought when it came  
to qualifying we'd pick up. It felt like it was going to be a good 
lap, but we've been a little off all day. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now we'll go to work on the race setup. I think we'll be good  
Sunday,'' he added. 
</P>
<P>
	The top 25 qualifiers nailed down starting spots in the race,  
with fan favorites Dale Earnhardt and Bill Elliott 17th and 18th, 
series runner-up Jarrett 23rd and John Andretti, last Sunday's 
winner in Martinsville, 24th. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990424.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 05:21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Movie Prices Protested in NY City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A committee of the New York City Council has  
called for a boycott of Friday night movies to protest what one 
member called the ``madness'' of the city's high ticket prices. 
</P>
<P>
	``For families living on a $30,000 a year budget, the cost of a  
night out at the movies would cost a day's wage after taxes, rent 
and utilities,'' said City Council Speaker Peter Vallone, who 
railed against the ``movie madness.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this year, Loews Cineplex Entertainment Co. raised  
ticket prices to $9.50 -- the nation's highest price -- leaving many 
movie lovers fuming. 
</P>
<P>
	Representatives of Loews did not return telephone messages left  
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time of the price hike, Vallone called for a federal  
investigation of the 1998 merger between the Loews Theaters and 
Cineplex Odeon chains. In February -- a few months after the merger 
-- the new conglomerate raised prices in Manhattan, ushering in the 
age of the $9.50 movie. 
</P>
<P>
	The City Council Committee on Consumer Affairs voted Friday to  
urge citizens to mount the boycott, a suggestion that might not 
appeal to today's teens. 
</P>
<P>
	Amy Liston, 14, and a group of girlfriends who ``took the day  
off'' from school Friday, nixed the idea. ``If we boycotted movies 
on Fridays, we wouldn't have any dates,'' she said. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
