<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 05:13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AT&AMP;T Makes $58B Bid For MediaOne </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- AT&AMP;T Corp.'s offer to buy the nation's  
fourth-largest cable company for $58 billion received a cool 
reaction from Wall Street this morning, with AT&AMP;T stock plunging as 
much as 7.5 percent as some analysts worried how the phone giant 
will absorb all its acquisitions. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation's largest telephone company delivered its unsolicited  
offer to Media One Thursday afternoon in an attempt to thwart a 
merger agreement between the cable-TV operator and No. 3 cable 
company Comcast reached last month. 
</P>
<P>
	If successful, AT&AMP;T would become the largest cable company in  
the United States with the ability to reach more than 40 percent of 
the nation's cable households, bolstering its emerging network for 
delivering local-phone service to Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T said its rival bid, a combination of cash and stock,  
exceeded the value of the Comcast deal by 17 percent, which was 
valued at about $49 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T chairman C. Michael Armstrong said he had no indication how  
MediaOne would respond to its bid, but called it ``a very superior 
offer'' to Comcast's. But some analysts wonder if the phone giant 
can swallow MediaOne after just completing its acquisition of cable 
company Tele-Communications Inc. last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong repeatedly reassured analysts in a teleconference this  
morning that a MediaOne acquisition would be its last major 
cable-TV deal. 
</P>
<P>
	``We absolutely do not have any plans, considerations, any  
thoughts or discussions for another signficant transaction,'' 
Armstrong said. He also stressed that AT&AMP;T plans significant cost 
cuts, including $2 billion in savings next year, to help the 
acquisition pay off. 
</P>
<P>
	MediaOne spokeswoman Cathy Fowler said the AT&AMP;T proposal is  
under review and ``We have nothing to add at this time.'' Comcast, 
based in Philadelphia, had no response to the offer. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of AT&AMP;T were down 5.1 percent, or $2.87 1/2 at $53.87 1/2 by  
late morning, recovering a bit from the day's lows in trading on 
the New York Stock Exchange. MediaOne's stock was up 11 percent, or 
$7.50, at $77 while Comcast shares were up $2.12 1/2 at $69.75. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T, with its acquisition of TCI, has 12.5 million cable  
subscribers. MediaOne has 5 million. Time Warner, currently the 
largest, has 12.6 million subscribers. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeffrey Kagan, an independent industry analyst in Atlanta, said  
such a move by AT&AMP;T was to be expected. ``Since AT&AMP;T decided that 
cable was the pathway of choice in the home, they need as much 
cable as they can get their hands on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	MediaOne is a spin-off of the U S West regional phone company,  
which decided in late 1997 to get out of the cable TV business. 
AT&AMP;T said the deal would expand its cable TV coverage in several 
key cities including Boston, Atlanta, Richmond, Va., and Los 
Angeles, putting it in 18 of the top 20 U.S. markets. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T has been in the market for cable TV companies because it  
plans to use the cable systems to deliver a combination of local 
and long-distance phone service, high-speed Internet access and 
interactive entertainment to millions of U.S. homes. Other cable 
companies have been merging to make them more competitive in 
offering the same package. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T has sought to offer local service by leasing telephone  
lines from the regional Baby Bells, but has stumbled in those 
efforts. 
</P>
<P>
	If AT&AMP;T's bid succeeds, it would reach more than 40 percent of  
U.S. cable households, estimated Gary Arlen, president of Arlen 
Communications Inc. in Bethesda, Md. ``It's a deal that could 
transform the telecom industry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That estimate includes cable companies that AT&AMP;T would own  
outright, along with partial ownerships and joint ventures. Most 
importantly, MediaOne owns 25 percent of Time Warner Entertainment, 
which controls Time Warner's cable business. 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong said in a conference call with reporters that the deal  
will also diversify AT&AMP;T's businesses. Consumer long-distance, 
which currently represents 45 percent to 50 percent of revenues, 
would fall to about 15 percent in the next four to five years, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T officials said they do not expect the deal to have any  
problems meeting regulatory approval and analysts agreed. 
</P>
<P>
	The counteroffer was made by Armstrong in a letter Thursday to  
Charles Lillis, chairman and chief executive of MediaOne. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T said the deal would save it $175 million to $200 million in  
the first year of operations. While there will be some work force 
reductions, AT&AMP;T officials wouldn't specify their scope. 
</P>
<P>
	The company acknowledged the cost of the deal would cut its  
profits by about 30 cents per share in the first full year after 
completion, but it said profits would rise after that. 
</P>
<P>
	Much of the profit reduction would be due to the issuance of an  
additional 626 million shares to help pay for the deal, along with 
the cost of borrowing money. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T earned $6.4 billion, or $2.38 per share in 1998, on revenue  
of $53.2 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T has structured the deal so that if its share price drops as  
much as 10 percent below $57, the amount paid MediaOne shareholders 
-- equivalent to $85 a share -- would not decline. 
</P>
<P>
	That could cost AT&AMP;T as much as $3.5 billion more in cash,  
Armstrong said. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T would also assume $4.5 billion in MediaOne debt and other  
obligations. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990424.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 05:21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Husband Arrested in Bludgeoning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- An investment manager was in critical condition  
Friday with a fractured skull after her husband allegedly 
bludgeoned her with a barbell while she slept. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said Aftab Islam may have become enraged after Theresa  
Havell asked him for a divorce. Islam, 58, was ordered held without 
bail on charges including attempted murder and assault. 
</P>
<P>
	Havell, 52, made a name for herself in investment circles while  
working for Neuberger Berman Management Inc., where she oversaw a 
$12 billion portfolio. She left there in 1996 and founded Havell 
Capital Management. She also had appeared as an occasional guest on 
CNN's ``Your Money'' show about personal finances. 
</P>
<P>
	Police were called to the couple's four-story townhouse on  
Manhattan's Upper East Side before dawn Thursday after receiving 
several calls, including one from the couple's teen-age daughter. 
</P>
<P>
	They found Havell beaten around the head and face with a  
barbell, Detective Walter Burnes said. 
</P>
<P>
	The victim's skull was fractured and she needed more than 100  
stitches to close head wounds. She also had several teeth knocked 
out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
