<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Even Home Ice May Not Save Ducks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- The Mighty Ducks, stunned in their series  
with Detroit, finally get some fan support. It's too bad their fans 
can't cross-check, deflect shots or clear the puck. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our fans are great but they can't go on the ice and make us  
play better,'' Anaheim's Teemu Selanne said after the Mighty Ducks 
fell behind 2-0 in the best-of-seven series. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we want to win, we've got to play at least at the level of  
our best hockey all season. We have a lot of things to fix and 
we've only got 36 hours to do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Ducks, who have won just once (1-7-2) since clinching a  
playoff berth, need more than a quick fix to compete against the 
two-time defending NHL champions Red Wings. 
</P>
<P>
	Anaheim, who returns home Sunday for Game 3, was outscored 10-4  
in the opening two games in Detroit, including a 5-1 drubbing 
Friday in the second game -- which wasn't even as close as the score 
might indicate. 
</P>
<P>
	``We better learn from our mistakes pretty quickly if we want to  
get back in this series,'' Selanne said. ``With the talent on that 
team, if they play well and we play badly it's all over.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His linemate, Paul Kariya, agreed.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're certainly not the more talented team in this series, so  
if we let them outwork us, they'll just kill us,'' said Kariya, who 
got off just one shot in Game 2 after his 429 this year were the 
second-most ever by a player in NHL history. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to simplify things and get our work ethic back. We're  
giving an honest effort,'' Kariya added. ``But when you're playing 
against the Stanley Cup champions and they're playing at 110 
percent, that's not going to do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Wings, whose sweep of the Mighty Ducks in the playoffs  
two years ago included three overtime wins, are 6-0 against Anaheim 
in the postseason. 
</P>
<P>
	``We do a lot of little things well in our own end,'' said  
Detroit's Brendan Shanahan, who had two goals and an assist in the 
Red Wings' four-goal opening period in Game 2. 
</P>
<P>
	``You saw guys still lying down to block shots and finishing  
checks, that's just as important for us. We always say, you come 
back to the bench you get as big a pat on the back for a goal as 
you do for a blocked shot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Shanahan expects the Mighty Ducks to be considerably more  
competitive on their home ice. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've really played well in their building,'' he said. ``So  
we know they're going to be excited and their fans are going to be 
excited, so it's going to be a really big game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While the Mighty Ducks have gone into a tailspin recently, the  
Red Wings are rolling. Detroit is 11-2-1 since acquiring Chris 
Chelios, Ulf Samuelsson, Wendel Clark and Bill Ranford at the trade 
deadline, and has outscored opponents 47-24. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
