<DOCNO> APW19990424.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 12:51:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Protesters Seek End of NATO Attacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Serbian-Americans joined with antiwar  
demonstrators outside the White House on Saturday to condemn the 
NATO bombing of Yugoslavia and urge renewed peace negotiations. 
</P>
<P>
	By mid-afternoon, the crowd at Lafayette Park grew to more than  
2,000 people, many of whom carried the red, white and blue flag of 
Serbia and denounced President Clinton and NATO leaders as 
warmongers. 
</P>
<P>
	Not far from where NATO officials were celebrating the  
alliance's 50th anniversary, the demonstrators released dozens of 
black balloons amid wild cheers. The balloons symbolized the lives 
lost in the NATO bombing, according to organizers. 
</P>
<P>
      	Some in the crowd carried signs saying ``KosovoVietnam'' and 	
</P>
<P>
          ``N-A-T-ONorth American Terrorist Organization.'' 	
</P>
<P>
	``The misguided polices of this administration and NATO are  
bringing a terrible calamity to our people,'' said Nikola 
Ristivojevich of Detroit. ``The solution won't be found in bombs 
but in serious negotiations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Slavia Pesakovic of Phoenix said the bombing of Yugoslavia could  
ignite another Vietnam. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am proud to be an American but I'm disgusted by this  
policy,'' Pesakovic said. ``Clinton has stepped into a small civil 
war and created a larger mess.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The rally dwarfed a smaller demonstration at Lafayette Park a  
day earlier by Albanian-Americans who supported the NATO bombing. 
</P>
<P>
	At one point Saturday, the protesters marched from the park down  
a local street and booed a group of NATO officials standing outside 
a downtown hotel. Some in the crowd yelled ``NATO means Nazis.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Like others in the crowd, Dave Stevens, of Highland Ind., said  
he is opposed to the leadership of Yugoslav President Slobodan 
Milosevic. But he said NATO bombing has become a unifying force for 
Serbian-Americans, which is helping Milosevic. 
</P>
<P>
	``Clinton is turning anti-Milosevic people into solid Milosevic  
people,'' Stevens said. ``They are making him a hero.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
