<DOCNO> APW19990424.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 00:41:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fan Returns Tatis Grand Slam Ball </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- All month long, fans in the Dodger Stadium  
pavilion seats have thrown back home runs hit by opposing players. 
Not this time. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Lerner, who works in the fish business and lives in Simi  
Valley, Calif., snagged the biggest catch of his life on Friday 
night -- even though someone else actually made the grab. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Lerner, who attended the game with his two sons, wound  
up with the ball Fernando Tatis hit into the left field pavilion 
for his second grand slam of the third inning. It made the 
Cardinals' third baseman the first player in history to hit two 
slams in one inning. 
</P>
<P>
	``This ball belongs in the Hall of Fame. That's what's  
important,'' Lerner said in a hallway leading to the Cardinals' 
clubhouse after the 12-5 victory over the Dodgers. ``This was 
history. I mean, this has never been done in the history of the 
game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When Tatis' second slam landed in the lower seats of the left  
field pavilion, a mad scramble for the ball ensued. A young fan got 
his hands on the precious ball first, but Lerner negotiated it away 
from him with offers of $40, $60 and then $80. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was bedlam there. Everybody knew what was going on,''  
Lerner said. ``I got a few bruises. 
</P>
<P>
	An usher who was on the scene wrote something on Lerner's ticket  
stub to authenticate it, then escorted Lerner and his party to the 
Cardinals' clubhouse, where the ball was placed inside a bag. It 
was then taken up to the stadium security department, where it was 
locked up until the end of the game. 
</P>
<P>
	After the final out, in front of a horde of media, Tatis  
autographed the uniform shirt he wore in the game and handed it to 
Lerner as a reward for the ball. Six baseballs were then brought 
out to Tatis, which the Cardinals' third baseman also autographed 
in front of Lerner and his sons, Kevin, 7, and Randy, 13. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just want to tell you that we're big-time baseball fans,''  
Lerner told Tatis, ``and I hope you put the ball in the Hall of 
Fame.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990424.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 15:42:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cubs Pitcher Hit in Face With Ball </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Trainer Dave Tumbas was in the Chicago Cubs  
lockerroom showing reporters Kerry Wood's surgical scar and 
explaining how his rehabilitation would unfold. Just as he was 
finishing the presentation, an urgent call summoned him to the 
field. 
</P>
<P>
	There, yet another pitching mishap awaited his attention  
Saturday -- pitcher Jon Lieber had been hit in the right eye with a 
ball thrown from the outfield during batting practice. 
</P>
<P>
	After he was helped off the field with a towel on his face,  
Lieber was taken to Northwestern Memorial Hospital where tests 
revealed no major damage to his eye. He will miss his scheduled 
Sunday start, however, and be re-evaluated Monday. Brad Woodall 
will start in his place 
</P>
<P>
	``It was just a freak thing,'' said Lieber, who sported a shiner  
after the game and also suffered some small broken bones in his 
nose. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had my back turned and the ball was in the air and it hit me  
square in the eye ball. I felt like I had been sucker punched.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The throw from Curtis Goodwin bounced first and then knocked  
Lieber down. 
</P>
<P>
	``I plan to make my next start after Sunday's,'' Lieber said.  
</P>
<P>
	The latest injury came one day after the pitching-shaky Cubs  
released Hideo Nomo, who declined to stay in the minors for two 
more starts on top of the three he'd already made. 
</P>
<P>
	What else can happen?  
</P>
<P>
	Pitchers Wood, Kevin Tapani, Jeremi Gonzalez, Terry Adams and  
Kurt Miller are all on the disabled list. And the bullpen, before 
four relievers combined Saturday with starter Terry Mulholland on 
an eight-hit shutout of the New York Mets, had been struggling. 
</P>
<P>
	Tapani will throw on the side Sunday. He underwent an MRI Friday  
that showed no structural damage in his sore right shoulder. His 
problem is muscular. 
</P>
<P>
	``They told me I could pitch another 10 years. The structure of  
the joint is healthy and it eliminated anything else,'' Tapani 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wood, who earlier this month underwent ``Tommy John surgery,''  
where a ligament from his wrist replaced the torn one in his elbow, 
is already doing extensive rehab -- range of motion and grip 
strength exercises and isometrics to keep his shoulder strong. He's 
also started lower leg work and conditioning drills. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year's NL Rookie of the Year said he watched a video replay  
of his own surgery and listened to the scraping of bone. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was not a good sound,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Wood, whose arm is still swollen, remained upbeat about his  
chances of returning and being a top pitcher again. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anytime you do something for a living and that's taken away  
from you, it changes your perspective,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
