<HEADLINE> NATO: 10 Yugoslav Generals Arrested </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- At least 10 fired Yugoslav generals have been  
placed under house arrest, a British spokesman said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Alastair Campbell, the press secretary for British Prime  
Minister Tony Blair, had no precise number for those being 
detained, saying only it was in ``double figures.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meeting with reporters, Campbell said that one sacked general  
was the former head of the army, fired shortly before the NATO air 
campaign against Yugoslavia began a month ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, NATO spokesman Jamie Shea was asked about such house  
arrests and said he had heard the same reports about Yugoslav 
President Slobodan Milosevic and his military leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	Shea said, ``There are many retired generals in Yugoslavia  
because Milosevic retires generals all the time. He doesn't seem to 
have much trust in them. I wonder if they have much trust in him.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
