<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NAACP Holds Sports Symposium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Having distinguished themselves on the playing  
field for decades, it's time for blacks to claim a greater share of 
the multibillion-dollar sports industry, Olympic gold medalist 
Jackie Joyner- Kersee said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Joyner-Kersee told a group of aspiring teen-age athletes to  
believe in themselves, but also begin to think beyond the actual 
sport. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's obvious that there's not a lot of African Americans that  
will get million-dollar endorsements,'' Joyner-Kersee said as a 
keynote speaker for a business and sports symposium. 
</P>
<P>
	The event, which attracted about 200 people, was sponsored by  
the Detroit chapter of the NAACP. 
</P>
<P>
	To Joyner-Kersee, the images of the few black athletes seen on  
television and in advertising is supposed to be sufficient 
representation for blacks, but isn't. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of us think that when you cross that line and win a gold  
medal, the endorsements are going to be there,'' said 
Joyner-Kersee, who retired in 1998. ``No, it doesn't work that 
way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Changes in advertising company management will have to come  
before it is reflected in advertising endorsements, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's where you come in,'' she told the youths. ``You have to  
be the ones that's in advertising that's making the decisions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although she won six Olympic medals, including golds in the  
heptathlon in 1988 and 1992 and the long jump in 1998, 
Joyner-Kersee said she still had a difficult time being marketed. 
</P>
<P>
	``The marketing of it all is terrible,'' she said. ``You don't  
hear about us until the Olympics. And that's sad.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Her solution was Elite Marketing, a sports marketing and  
management company she started in 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	``I always wanted to be a woman of power,'' she said. ``So I put  
my money into my own company.'' More than $500,000 to be exact, 
because she believes there is a major opportunity. 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday's youth-targeted symposium follows the national  
direction of getting young people more involved in the 
organization. 
</P>
<P>
	``The goal is to allow the young athletes here to see that they  
can do more than to just play the game but to own the game,'' said 
John E. Johnson Jr., executive director of the Detroit NAACP. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson said it is time for blacks to get involved in other  
aspects of sports, such as front office administration and 
coaching. 
</P>
<P>
	There was plenty of advice being given to the attentive youth by  
black coaches, successful businessmen and players, who included 
former Detroit Pistons player John Salley. 
</P>
<P>
	``Never relax,'' he said. ``Always be 10 times faster, 10 times  
better and 10 times smarter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since leaving the basketball court and becoming a businessman,  
Salley shared how he had to learn some expensive lessons. 
</P>
<P>
	``I got burned enough to learn not to touch the stove,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Beyond that, the managing director and chief investment officer  
of No Limit Enterprises, an entertainment and sports conglomerate, 
told the youths to make choices for themselves and be different. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's about empowering yourself for the 21st century, which  
means gaining knowledge,'' said Leland Hardy, the young executive 
of the black-owned company that generated over $400 million in 
revenue last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
