<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IAAF Panel Delays Slaney Verdict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MONTE CARLO, Monaco (AP) -- Mary Slaney will have to wait a  
little longer before track and field's ruling body rules on her 
drug case. 
</P>
<P>
	An arbitration panel was expected to rule Saturday on whether  
the star distance runner took a banned substance before the 1996 
U.S. Olympic trials. Now, the three-member panel won't decide until 
Monday at the earliest. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman for the International Amateur Athletic Federation  
told The Associated Press the panel is re-examining evidence. 
</P>
<P>
	The hearing will continue despite an attempt by Slaney's lawyers  
to stop it. They have sued the IAAF and U.S. Olympic Committee, 
which administered the original test. 
</P>
<P>
	Slaney, considered the greatest women's distance runner in U.S.  
history, gave a urine sample during the 1996 U.S. Olympic trials 
that showed a testosterone-epitestosterone (T-E) ratio above the 
6-1 limit. 
</P>
<P>
	The IAAF suspended Slaney, claiming USA Track and Field was slow  
to investigate. 

federation cleared the runner.  
</P>
<P>
	The IAAF also cleared Slaney to compete but referred the case to  
arbitration. 
</P>
<P>
	The T-E ratio is used by dozens of sports. It detects the  
presence of testosterone, a naturally occurring muscle-building 
hormone that is also taken in concentrated form to improve 
performance. 
</P>
<P>
	A T-E ratio should normally be about 1-1, but Slaney's original  
sample was reportedly higher than the 6-1 ratio that triggers an 
investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Slaney, 40, says recent research shows the T-E test is  
unreliable for women in their late 30s or 40s who are taking the 
birth control pill, an argument refuted by the IAAF. 
</P>
<P>
	The arbitration panel originally met in January, but reconvened  
after lawyers from both sides requested more time to collect 
evidence. 
</P>
<P>
	The three judges on the panel are: chairman Christoph Vedder of  
Germany, Robert Ellicott of Australia and Lin Kokloh of Singapore. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
