<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- People still smoke in public places like  
classrooms and sometimes even elevators in Mexico -- at least for 
now. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress approved a bill Friday that would ban smoking in  
government offices and public buildings as part of changes to the 
country's health codes. It still must be approved by the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	But while internal regulations made the smoking ban effective on  
the floor of congress as of Friday, some legislators continued to 
light up in the legislative building, the daily newspaper Reforma 
reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Mexican currently bans smoking on most domestic airplane flights  
and in hospitals. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Prosecutors have arrested a man on a U.S.  
extradition warrant for his alleged participation in a prostitution 
ring that took underage Mexican women to southern Florida and 
forced them to work as prostitutes. 
</P>
<P>
	The Attorney General's Office said it had arrested Abel Cadena  
Sosa, a Mexican citizen, on charges of international trafficking of 
minors and keeping the women and girls prisoners for the purpose of 
prostitution in Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	The women and girls -- some as young as 13 -- were promised jobs  
and a new start in the United States but instead found themselves 
enslaved in a prostitution ring run by the Cadena family. 
</P>
<P>
	Five members of that family face charges, most of which carry  
10-year sentences for each illegal immigrant smuggled and kept in 
servitude. The case was uncovered in November when two 15-year-old 
girls escaped from the home where they were kept as prisoners. 
</P>
<P>
	Abel Cadena was arrested this week in the Gulf coast state of  
Veracruz -- where many of the women were from -- and taken to Mexico 
City, where he faces preliminary extradition hearings. The 
hearings, and subsequent appeals, could delay an extradition for 
months or even years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
