<DOCNO> APW19990424.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 08:52:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Push On for Vote on Campaign Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Campaign reform is back, the idea whose time  
never seems to come, although the sponsors always say this is it. 
That's what they're saying now, as they look for routes around 
roadblocks in the Republican Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	In the House, the push is on, largely by Democrats, to compel  
through petition action that the GOP leadership doesn't want at 
this point. With 218 signatures, a majority, a bill can be forced 
to a vote. 
</P>
<P>
	Under similar pressure last year, Republican leaders agreed to  
bring it up and the House approved a campaign finance bill, 
252-179. It was a safe vote for a popular cause; everybody knew the 
Senate wouldn't pass it. 
</P>
<P>
	It might be approved there, too, if it came to a vote. Fifty-two  
senators voted for the measure on a preliminary motion last time. 
But Republican opponents have filibustered to block it before, and 
would again. It would take 60 votes to get past them. 
</P>
<P>
	House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., has promised a vote on the  
campaign bill again this year, but not yet. He wants to wait until 
later in the session, after appropriations and other major measures 
have been handled. 
</P>
<P>
	The campaign bill would ban so-called soft money, the unlimited  
donations that can be made to political parties. The illegal 
foreign contributions to the Democrats during President Clinton's 
1996 re-election campaign were in the form of soft-money donations. 
</P>
<P>
	To underline that point, the Senate version of the bill would  
specifically prohibit contributions from foreign governments or 
foreign nationals to any U.S. election campaign -- federal, state or 
local. 
</P>
<P>
	The measures also would restrict the growing use of issue ads,  
in which corporations or unions skirt the bar against direct 
spending on campaigns by buying radio or television ads, supposedly 
on issues but effectively against a candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	Advocacy groups -- read special interests -- could continue  
advertising in campaigns but would have to disclose their 
expenditures and the sources of the money. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need to start somewhere and that place is here and that  
time is now,'' said Rep. Richard A. Gephardt of Missouri, the House 
Democratic leader, urging prompt action. 
</P>
<P>
	He said Republican leaders have stifled reform bills for two  
years. ``First it was death by amendment,'' Gephardt said. ``Now it 
is death by delay. Well, it is now or never.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although it may be neither. The sponsors say they're not  
quitting, no matter the setbacks. ``The American campaign finance 
system is manifestly corrupt,'' said Sen. Russ Feingold, D-Wis. 
``So we are back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Republican Sen. John McCain of Arizona is the lead sponsor of  
the Senate bill, giving a bipartisan stamp to a bill that has that 
word in its title, ``The Bipartisan Campaign Reform Act of 1999.'' 
There is a GOP sponsor in the House, too: Rep. Christopher Shays of 
Connecticut. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain is a reformer with heavy fund-raising demands of his own  
this time, running for president in a crowded, high-cost campaign 
for the Republican nomination in 2000. He's reported raising $1.8 
million, and has transferred another $2 million from his Senate 
campaign to his current quest. 
</P>
<P>
	It's a beginning, but no match for the $7.6 million reported  
March 31 by Texas Gov. George W. Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	Vice President Al Gore raised $8.9 million for his Democratic  
campaign, toward a target of $55 million. 
</P>
<P>
	For Bush, the fund-raising budget may be $50 million, enough to  
do without federal campaign aid, which carries with it limits on a 
candidate's spending in running for the nomination, overall and 
state by state. 
</P>
<P>
	By forgoing federal campaign money, he wouldn't be bound by  
limits on spending in the early primaries, the ones that really 
count, with big state primaries lined up on March 7 and the 
nomination likely to be won at the start. 
</P>
<P>
	That doesn't fit the system Congress designed in 1974.  
State-by-state spending ceilings work when the campaign progresses 
from state to state. But not when competition is going to be 
concentrated, and probably over, in the first weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	There's been no talk of changing that system.  
</P>
<P>
	--------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE: Walter R. Mears, vice president and special  
correspondent for The Associated Press, has reported on Washington 
and national politics for more than 30 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
