<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-24 17:12:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Diary Indicates Shooting Well Planned  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLETON, Colo. (AP) -- A diary found in one of the Colorado  
gunmen's home indicates that a year of planning went into the 
shooting spree, and the local sheriff says some of the blame must 
fall on the shooter's parents. Along with the diary, investigators 
found a shotgun barrel on a dresser and bomb-making materials. 
Jefferson County Sheriff John Stone wouldn't say in which gunman's 
home these items were found. ``A lot of this stuff was clearly 
visible and the parents should have known,'' said Stone. ``I think 
parents should be accountable for their kid's actions.'' The 
shooting at Columbine High School claimed 15 lives, including the 
two gunmen. 

</P>
<P>
	Friends Mourn Teen Killed in Colo.  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLETON, Colo. (AP) -- Friends of 17-year-old Rachel Scott  
remembered her as more than just a victim of the shooting spree 
that hit Columbine High: to one, she was a fun prom date, to 
another, a budding actress and playwright. And suddenly she was 
gone. On Saturday, weeping and hollow-eyed, they mourned her in a 
sad parade, their reminiscences melting together into a portrait of 
a truly extraordinary girl. ``I was so proud of that girl. She was 
talented and beautiful, and I know that she's with us still,'' said 
Paula Reed, Ms. Scott's forensics teacher. ``But she took part of 
me with her.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Oil Will Flow To Serbs, Russia Says  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- On the second day of their summit, NATO  
leaders said today that military commanders were laying plans under 
orders issued last night for sea searches to ``switch off the oil 
tap'' fueling Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's military 
machine. But Russia, angry about 32 days of airstrikes against 
Yugoslavia, indicated it would ignore an embargo. ``According to 
international law, sanctions cannot be imposed unless they are 
approved by the (U.N.) Security Council,'' Russian Foreign Minister 
Igor Ivanov said on a trip to Egypt. ``We will continue delivering 
oil in keeping with our international commitments.'' Russia and 
Libya are Yugoslavia's key oil suppliers. 

</P>
<P>
	Nuclear Launch Codes Left Behind  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton departed the NATO summit in  
such haste today that he left behind perhaps the most important 
piece of luggage in the world -- the ``nuclear football.'' The 
president's military aide, who constantly shadows Clinton and 
carries the briefcase containing U.S. nuclear launch codes, was 
mistakenly left at the International Trade Center when Clinton's 
motorcade sped off 45 minutes early and without notice. The aide 
walked the 4 1/2 blocks back to the White House without incident. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Expecting Kosovo Refugees  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Kosovo refugees are being processed in  
Macedonia by State Department and U.S. immigration officials, and 
thousands will be flown from Macedonia to the United States to join 
relatives who immigrated earlier, the White House said today. The 
United States is taking in some 20,000 ethnic Albanians of the 
estimated 800,000 to 1 million who fled or were forced to leave 
Kosovo by Serb troops. Priority is being given to refugees with 
relatives in the United States. 

</P>
<P>
	Court Bars Use of Rival Trademark  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A federal appeals court outlawed a stealth  
weapon in the Internet commerce wars by forbidding companies from 
using their rivals' trademarks to steal business through Web sites. 
The ruling from the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals involves the 
practice of including a competitors' trademark or brand name in an 
Internet site, either as the address or through what are known as 
``meta-tags,'' which are embedded in a Web page's coding and will 
point a search program toward a particular site. 

</P>
<P>
	Coyotes Tie Series  
</P>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Shane Doan scored the winning goal 8:58 into  
overtime today, and the Coyotes beat the St. Louis Blues 4-3 to end 
goalie Grant Fuhr's playoff domination of their franchise and tie 
the first-round series 1-1. It was a dramatic comeback for the 
Coyotes, who had their only lead at 3-2 on Keith Carney's 
unassisted goal late in the third period, only to see Pavol Demitra 
tie it with 3:18 left. Had the Coyotes lost, they would have faced 
a 2-0 deficit going into Game 3 tomorrow and the prospect of 
possibly not returning to their home arena. 

</P>
<P>
	Giants Beat Rockies  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Charlie Hayes hit a two-run triple in his  
first game back from a suspension and Shawn Estes pitched seven 
strong innings today to give the San Francisco Giants a 8-4 win 
against the Colorado Rockies. Hayes went 2-for-4 and also scored 
two runs in his return from a four-game suspension for charging 
Arizona pitcher Todd Stottlemyre from second base last week. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
